Dear MOH, is it MOH intention or SOP to make elderly wait for at least 3 hours for vaccination?   Me, my hubby and kid went all the way from the south to the north to fetch my mum from Yishun to Woodlands Galaxy CC on Saturday 27 Feb. My mum waited 1 hr for a queue number ticket. The PA staff (I assume) advised the crowd to return home, register for a new date again and come back another day. Some were dismayed and argued with the staff, some feedbacked they don’t know technology. I told the staff that “this is last thing I wanna hear after coming all the way here”.  I was bewildered, if you have expected weekends to be so crowded and tedious waiting, why set these seniors appointments on Saturday? Not to mention young people are also allowed to register during this period which I thought is supposed to prioritize the seniors... if not for the staff to suggest we could collect a queue tix, leave for dinner and come back 2 hrs later to take the jab, I would be more annoyed. He has provided an App to show the queue status.   After returning to the CC, my mum had to wait for another hour seated in the indoor auditorium to get the jab.. we were all beat and exhausted, I am sure other seniors and their caregivers also feel the same.

I can appreciate how SG has just started on the covid vaccination initiative for the elderlies.  someone just came to my door this morning... volunteers for the Covid-19 vaccination... supposedly meant to help elderlies make their vaccination appointments.   Regarding these volunteers who came to my door... How could MOH release / divulge my dad's personal data to them?  It wasn't a random knock on each residence, but they specifically came to look up my dad because they were given his name and address, and not sure what other data.  These are volunteers... Not MOH staff.. How could they be authorised to handle personal data?   Would this be considered a breach of PDPA?  And we have had cases of scammers/pranksters going around carrying out their act of deceit in the name of MOH during this pandemic.  It is unnerving to get strangers coming to one's doorstep without being first informed by MOH regarding this form of enthusiastic outreach towards the elderlies.  I look forward to receiving a verification from MOH at the soonest possible.  Gan Kim Yong Gan Kim Yong

It has been more than half a year ago since our circuit breaker. The world lost the tussle to COVID-19. Every country was affected. We probably knew someone who was badly hit by the virus in one way or another. We lost our connectivity abroad. Some of us lost even more than that. Today, Singapore is on the road to recovery. We have the people and we know what needs to get done. Bring back our lives and build back better from it. I am extremely moved that the first dedicated facility for travellers has been opened. We have proven we can manage the risk and yet we can't afford to shake the confidence that we have in our community. I note that the task force constantly remind us to stay vigilant and we will indeed continue to stay alert. We have to stay safe and we have each other to cover our backs. This is our responsibility to save lives and we have what it takes.  We will be able to get it done. We have friends and neighbours who will support us and get behind us.
May All Be Well, Speedy Recovery, Stay Safe and Auspicious !🙏🙏🙏🍀🍀🍀💐💐💐❤❤❤😍😊😄🌻🌷🌺🌸🌼🌹🍐🍓🍑🍒🍇🍍💖

MOH advise that we check with our doctor to see if we are suitable to take the vaccination but which doctor? The doctor at the pte neighbourhood clinic I pop into once in a while when I could not sleep, experienced tummy upset, or minor accidental injuries? Or the doctor in the cardiac clinic who sees me twice a year? Or the doctor in the otolaryngology clinic whose prescription solved my problem but caused another problem which still afflicts me to this day three months later?   I would think that MOH should be the "doctor" to advise me on whether I should take the vaccination as MOH has all my medical details in its databank. MOH can and should go through all the medical records of its patients and advise all these patients appropriately.
When can I have SINOVAC as my choice?  Everything about this vaccine is not announced to the public.
Beware. There are phishers and scammers sending SMSes telling seniors of bogus appointments for the vaccination with MOH (name only) as sender. Name only SMS should have been BANNED!
I am willing to be vaccinated immediately if possible.
Thenan Subramaniam
Wee Yew Tiong Jovia Lee

Is global mass vaccination really the best and only way forward? . Or is there some herd mentality among global leaders, and public health professionals, with biased favor for "prestigious" "high-tech" vaccines, instead of "low-tech" N95 masks? Or even some profit-driven interest in pushing widespread vaccination instead of widespread N95 mask usage? . Have countries like Singapore tried getting people involved in border control, to have strict N95 mask protocols, before deeming border leaks as inevitable? Or are people like bus drivers and quarantine-hotel staff free to wear whatever random low-effectiveness piece of cloth that they fancy? . Wouldn't widespread N95 mask usage effectively lead to "herd immunity"? (Instead of other low-efficiency masks that keep the virus circulating in lower doses that reduce disease severity and thus evade detection.) . Vaccines: ~$20 each (cost of distribution not yet included). 02月13日 新加坡疫情统计数据报告：新增确诊病例09，累计确诊病例59,833，(包括：累计境外及客工确诊病例56,843、累计社区确诊病例2,943、累计旅客确诊病例47)，累计重症住院病例34(其中累计危重症病例1)，累计死亡病例29，累计确诊轻症隔离病例119，累计治愈病例59,604，死亡率0.04%。 Roylab Stats World Map全球新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例超108,953,518，累计死亡病例超2,400,408，死亡率2.20%。 美国新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例28,125,957，累计死亡病例492,933，死亡率1.75%。占全球确诊率25.81%，占全球死亡率20.53%。马来西亚排列49、中国排列84、新加坡排列96。 疫苗作为抵御病毒全球大流行的终极武器，被人们寄予厚望，疫苗是解决新冠肺炎病毒最根本办法，不管哪个国家做出来疫苗，都不能供应全世界，这需要互相学习，且做出来后取长补短，可能要由很多厂家来生产，才能够供应全世界。世界卫生组织（WHO）呼吁全球合作伙伴共同发起全球合作加速开发、生产、公平获取新冠肺炎防控新工具的倡议。新冠病毒是一种新病毒，疫苗研发有很多不确定因素，多种技术路线并进才是多保险方案，为了更大限度地提升疫苗研发的成功率，在梳理分析不同的技术基础和可能性之后，科研攻关组布局了病毒的灭活疫苗、核酸疫苗、重组蛋白疫苗、腺病毒载体疫苗、减毒流感病毒载体疫苗这样5条技术路线。目前国际上绝大多数疫苗都处于临床研究阶段，中国有4种疫苗即腺病毒载体疫苗和3种灭活疫苗；美国有3种包括莫德纳药企的mRNA疫苗、辉瑞药企的mRNA疫苗、Inovio药企的DNA载体疫苗；英国有1种为牛津大学的腺病毒载体疫苗。 灭活疫苗是最传统的经典技术路线：即在体外培养新冠病毒，然后将其灭活，使之没有毒性，但这些病毒仍能刺激人体产生抗体，使免疫细胞记住病毒的模样，灭活疫苗的优点是制备方法简单快速，安全性比较高，它是应对急性疾病传播通常采用的手段，其缺点如接种剂量大、免疫期短、免疫途径单一等，而有时会造成抗体依赖增强效应（ADE），使病毒感染加重，会导致疫苗研发失败的严重不良反应。 腺病毒载体疫苗是用经过改造后无害的腺病毒作为载体，装入新冠病毒的S蛋白基因，制成腺病毒载体疫苗，刺激人体产生抗体。S蛋白是新冠病毒入侵人体细胞的关键“钥匙”，无害的腺病毒戴上S蛋白的“帽子”，假装自己很“凶”，让人体产生免疫记忆。优点是：安全、高效、引发的不良反应少。这种疫苗有成功先例，缺点，重组病毒载体疫苗研发需要考虑如何克服“预存免疫”，大多数人成长过程中曾感染过5型腺病毒，体内可能存在能中和腺病毒载体的抗体，从而可能攻击载体、降低疫苗效果。 核酸疫苗包括mRNA疫苗和DNA疫苗，是将编码S蛋白的基因，mRNA或DNA直接注入人体，利用人体细胞在人体内合成S蛋白，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于把一份记录详细的病毒档案交给人体的免疫系统。优点是：研制时不需要合成蛋白质或病毒，流程简单，安全性相对比较高，核酸疫苗是全世界都在积极探索的疫苗研发新技术，缺点是：无成功先例，多数国家无法大规模生产，可能因价格较贵而难以普及到低收入国家。 重组蛋白疫苗，也称基因工程重组亚单位疫苗，是通过基因工程方法，大量生产新冠病毒最有可能作为抗原的S蛋白，把它注射到人体，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于不生产完整病毒，而是单独生产很多新冠病毒的关键部件“钥匙”，将其交给人体的免疫系统认识。优点是：安全、高效、可规模化生产，有成功先例，重组亚单位疫苗的缺点是需要找到一个好的表达系统，这很困难。 病毒减毒活疫苗是非常重要的一类疫苗，是低毒性流感病毒戴上新冠病毒S蛋白“帽子”后形成的融合病毒，可以一石二鸟，既能防流感又能防新冠。 每逢佳节倍思亲，挥之不去的怀念，抹之不掉的回忆，音容不忘永常在。树欲静而风不止、子欲养而亲不在。高山仰望止于前、大海无边渡于岸。沉舟侧伴千帆过、病树前头万木春。子鼠疫年千家災、丑牛苗种万民安。

02月10日 新加坡疫情统计数据报告：新增确诊病例15，累计确诊病例59,794，(包括：累计境外及客工确诊病例56,809、累计社区确诊病例2,938、累计旅客确诊病例47)，累计重症住院病例36(其中累计危重症病例1)，累计死亡病例29，累计确诊轻症隔离病例156，累计治愈病例59,526，死亡率0.04%。 Roylab Stats World Map全球新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例超107,634,754，累计死亡病例超2,358,122，死亡率2.19%。 美国新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例27,805,113，累计死亡病例479,839，死亡率1.72%。占全球确诊率25.83%，占全球死亡率20.34%。马来西亚排列49、中国排列84、新加坡排列96。 灭活疫苗是最传统的经典技术路线：即在体外培养新冠病毒，然后将其灭活，使之没有毒性，但这些病毒仍能刺激人体产生抗体，使免疫细胞记住病毒的模样，灭活疫苗的优点是制备方法简单快速，安全性比较高，它是应对急性疾病传播通常采用的手段，其缺点如接种剂量大、免疫期短、免疫途径单一等，而有时会造成抗体依赖增强效应（ADE），使病毒感染加重，会导致疫苗研发失败的严重不良反应。 腺病毒载体疫苗是用经过改造后无害的腺病毒作为载体，装入新冠病毒的S蛋白基因，制成腺病毒载体疫苗，刺激人体产生抗体。S蛋白是新冠病毒入侵人体细胞的关键“钥匙”，无害的腺病毒戴上S蛋白的“帽子”，假装自己很“凶”，让人体产生免疫记忆。优点是：安全、高效、引发的不良反应少。这种疫苗有成功先例，缺点，重组病毒载体疫苗研发需要考虑如何克服“预存免疫”，大多数人成长过程中曾感染过5型腺病毒，体内可能存在能中和腺病毒载体的抗体，从而可能攻击载体、降低疫苗效果。

Mr Wong, co-chair of the Government’s Covid-19 task force, said that people who decline or do not book a slot for the vaccination when offered because they are still undecided must “accept the consequences” that if they change their minds later, a ready supply of vaccines may not be available.  Overcoming public distrust of the Covid-19 vaccines is a major obstacle to governments’ efforts worldwide in persuading enough people to get vaccinated to achieve herd immunity.  The acceptance of the vaccines depends on public trust and confidence in the safety and efficacy of vaccines and immunisation, the health system, healthcare professionals and the wider vaccine research community.  These are all important factors that influence a person’s decision-making process.  Furthermore, for vaccine uptake to increase, the public must be inspired through authentic communication and dialogue — something the public health agencies here, including the national task force, has arguably failed to achieve.  The public health agencies should have launched robust public outreach efforts that encourage various communities, including religious groups, to address the questions and concerns that these communities may have.  Even if the public does not fully trust the science of the vaccines, social norms in the communities can go a long way in persuading people to get vaccinated.  If individuals believe that all the people they love and the people who care for them think that they should get the vaccine, they are more likely to be influenced to get it.  The public’s trust and confidence are important in light of adverse overseas news reports about the side effects of the vaccines, with people having died after getting the shots.  Another hurdle our public health officials have to overcome is the people’s primary concern: Whether the vaccines are appropriately tested for safety, efficacy and effectiveness before the authorities such as the Health Sciences Authority approve them for use.  We have been in this pandemic for around a year and the vaccines have been developed fairly quickly (it normally takes a few years), so it is natural for people to be suspicious of what is unknown.  The public health agencies must work to "immunise" people against misinformation.  This could be accomplished only if there is trust resulting from authentic relationships between the Government and the people.  Vaccine hesitancy is a problem of dignity as much as of the abundance of falsehoods.  Singaporeans want to have their choices respected, not to be told that they cannot choose which vaccines to take because they rejected one the first time.  It would be helpful for the national task force to re-examine its communication and engagement strategy for the vaccination programme, with the view to build up the public’s trust. Scientists tells the truth but politicians suggests otherwise!  ACADEMY OF MEDICINE SINGAPORE, NATIONAL CENTRE FOR INFECTIOUS DISEASE AND COLLEGE OF PHYSICIANS https://www.ams.edu.sg/view-pdf.aspx?file=media%5C5558_fi_168.pdf&ofile=Period+of+Infectivity+Position+Statement+%28final%29+23-5-20.pdf  Sars-CoV-2 virus has not been isolated, purified and cultured. What we get to see are animated cartoon images of the spiked virus.  When the Ct value was 30 or higher (i.e. when viral load is low), no viable virus (based on being able to culture the virus) has been found. In addition, virus could not be isolated or cultured after day 11 of illness — SARS-CoV-2 Virus has not been isolated or cultured, so what is the vaccine for?  PCR machines can't diagnose an infection, it is simply a research tool.  COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. (1)  PCR tests cannot detect viral loads and are prone to false positives. (2)  A positive PCR test does not mean that an individual is infected nor infective. (3)  In fact approximately 90% of the PCR positive ‘cases’ are false positives. We therefore have no second wave and no pandemic. (4 , 5)  The government’s report estimates a false positive rate of between 0.8 to 4.0 % using data from other viral infections – not from covid (6)  Viral fragments may remain in people’s bodies for several weeks following recovery from infection. (7)  The crisis will never end if we are waiting for zero positive tests. Everyone has probably had a cold caused by a coronavirus and will likely have a few viral fragments matching those of the cousin SARS-CoV-2 virus (8)  Testing healthy asymptomatic individuals is non-sensical, unscientific and a colossal waste of money.  Antibody testing is not the gold standard as many people have T-cell immunity, and antibodies may not circulate following recovery from infection.  Viral RNA detection by PCR does not equate to infectiousness or viable virus — PCR testings are scientifically meaningless because it is not a diagnostic tool, so why keep testing and testing people with false positive results?

It is wonderful news that there are no local cases detected for 4 days in a row! Could you please let us know roughly how many locals in the community have been tested in the last 4-5 days? COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. (1)  PCR tests cannot detect viral loads and are prone to false positives. (2)  A positive PCR test does not mean that an individual is infected nor infective. (3)  In fact approximately 90% of the PCR positive ‘cases’ are false positives. We therefore have no second wave and no pandemic. ACADEMY OF MEDICINE SINGAPORE, NATIONAL CENTRE FOR INFECTIOUS DISEASE AND COLLEGE OF PHYSICIANS https://www.ams.edu.sg/view-pdf.aspx?file=media%5C5558_fi_168.pdf&ofile=Period+of+Infectivity+Position+Statement+%28final%29+23-5-20.pdf  Sars-CoV-2 virus has not been isolated, purified and cultured. What we get to see are animated cartoon images of the spiked virus.  When the Ct value was 30 or higher (i.e. when viral load is low), no viable virus (based on being able to culture the virus) has been found. In addition, virus could not be isolated or cultured after day 11 of illness — SARS-CoV-2 Virus has not been isolated or cultured, so what is the vaccine for?  PCR machines can't diagnose an infection, it is simply a research tool.  COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. (1)  PCR tests cannot detect viral loads and are prone to false positives. (2)  A positive PCR test does not mean that an individual is infected nor infective. (3)  In fact approximately 90% of the PCR positive ‘cases’ are false positives. We therefore have no second wave and no pandemic. (4 , 5)  The government’s report estimates a false positive rate of between 0.8 to 4.0 % using data from other viral infections – not from covid (6)  Viral fragments may remain in people’s bodies for several weeks following recovery from infection. (7)  The crisis will never end if we are waiting for zero positive tests. Everyone has probably had a cold caused by a coronavirus and will likely have a few viral fragments matching those of the cousin SARS-CoV-2 virus (8)  Testing healthy asymptomatic individuals is non-sensical, unscientific and a colossal waste of money.  Antibody testing is not the gold standard as many people have T-cell immunity, and antibodies may not circulate following recovery from infection.  Viral RNA detection by PCR does not equate to infectiousness or viable virus — PCR testings are scientifically meaningless because it is not a diagnostic tool, so why keep testing and testing people?

Dear In-Charge,  I would like to extend my sincere gratitude to the multi-ministry taskforce, frontline workers and all who have worked so hard to keep us safe.   Looking at the rising trend of people testing positive after the 14 days quarantine, would the taskforce consider subjecting ALL travellers (including Singaporeans and Permanent Residents) arriving in our nation (not only those arriving from the United Kingdom and South Africa) to an additional seven days of self-isolation (or even additional 14 days) at their place of residence, following their 14-day stay-home notice period?  A closer look at the symptoms of travellers during and after their isolation period is also critical and for those travellers who have mild symptoms even after a month, would the taskforce consider re-testing and extending their isolation period?  As for the domitory workers, would the taskforce also consider having tighter controls and having a peer buddy system or closer supervision by their supervisors to monitor if they have any symptoms or feeling unwell.  This has been on my mind for a long time and I would like to voice out my concerns due to the increasing imported cases, locally transmitted cases and asymptomatic cases in our nation.  Thank you very much for your kind attention.  Best regards, Shu Min

Case 59028, a 24 year-old male Korean national, is a Work Permit holder who works at Azur at Crowne Plaza Changi Airport (75 Airport Boulevard). His job entails delivering pre-packed meals to air crew and hotel guests. He does not interact with diners at Azur.*  He tested positive for a pooled swab during Rostered Routine Testing (RRT) on 2 January, and was tested again on 4 January. On the same day, he started to develop acute respiratory infection (ARI) symptoms. His individual test result came back positive for COVID-19 infection on 5 January, and he was conveyed in an ambulance to the National Centre for Infectious Diseases. His serological test result has come back negative, indicating that this is likely a current infection. He has also tested preliminarily positive for the B117 strain, and is pending further confirmatory tests

Every Scary Things You're Being Told Depends On The Unreliable PCR Test https://youtu.be/6ny9nNFHQsY  ACADEMY OF MEDICINE SINGAPORE, NATIONAL CENTRE FOR INFECTIOUS DISEASE AND COLLEGE OF PHYSICIANS https://www.ams.edu.sg/view-pdf.aspx?file=media%5C5558_fi_168.pdf&ofile=Period+of+Infectivity+Position+Statement+%28final%29+23-5-20.pdf  Sars-CoV-2 virus has not been isolated and purified. When the Ct value was 30 or higher (i.e. when viral load is low), no viable virus (based on being able to culture the virus) has been found. COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. (1)  PCR tests cannot detect viral loads and are prone to false positives. (2)  A positive PCR test does not mean that an individual is infected nor infective. (3)  In fact approximately 90% of the PCR positive ‘cases’ are false positives. We therefore have no second wave and no pandemic. (4 , 5)  The government’s report estimates a false positive rate of between 0.8 to 4.0 % using data from other viral infections – not from covid (6)  Viral fragments may remain in people’s bodies for several weeks following recovery from infection. Antibody testing is not the gold standard as many people have T-cell immunity, and antibodies may not circulate following recovery from infection.  Viral RNA detection by PCR does not equate to infectiousness or viable virus — PCR testings are scientifically meaningless because it is not a diagnostic tool, so why keep testing and testing people?

Leading Canadian Health Expert Outraged at Government Response to COVID  Dr. Roger Hodkinson, MA, MB, FRCPC, FCAP, CEO and medical director of Western Medical Assessments, spoke at the Edmonton City Council Community and Public Services Committee meeting on Nov. 13 about the city’s move to extend its face-covering bylaw. He was listed as speaker number 95 on the meeting agenda.  Dr. Hodkinson was trained at Cambridge University in the UK. He is ex-president of the pathology section of the Medical Association. He was the chairman of the Royal College of Physicians of Canada Examination Committee and Pathology in Ottawa, Canada.  Here’s the transcript of Hodkinson’s testimony:  This is Dr. Hodkinson, I just wanted to let you know I’m standing by. OK, well we would love to hear from you, the floor is yours. Thank you very much. I do appreciate the opportunity to address you on this very important matter. What I’m going to say is lay language, and blunt. It is counter-narrative, and so you don’t immediately think I’m a quack, I’m going to briefly outline my credentials so that you can understand where I’m coming from in terms of knowledge base in all of this. I’m a medical specialist in pathology which includes virology. I trained at Cambridge University in the UK. I’m the ex-president of the pathology section of the Medical Association. I was previously an assistant professor in the Faculty of Medicine doing a lot of teaching. I was the chairman of the Royal College of Physicians of Canada Examination Committee and Pathology in Ottawa, but more to the point I’m currently the chairman of a biotechnology company in North Carolina selling the COVID-19 test. And [inaudible] you might say I know a little bit about all of this. The bottom line is simply this: There is utterly unfounded public hysteria driven by the media and politicians. It’s outrageous. This is the greatest hoax ever perpetrated on an unsuspecting public. There is absolutely nothing that can be done to contain this virus. Other than protecting older, more vulnerable people. It should be thought of as nothing more than a bad flu season. This is not Ebola. It’s not SARS. It’s politics playing medicine and that’s a very dangerous game. There is no action of any kind needed other than what happened last year when we felt unwell. We stayed home, we took chicken noodle soup, we didn’t visit granny and we decided when we would return to work. We didn’t need anyone to tell us. Masks are utterly useless. There is no evidence base for their effectiveness whatsoever. Paper masks and fabric masks are simply virtue-signaling. They’re not even worn effectively most of the time. It’s utterly ridiculous. Seeing these unfortunate, uneducated people — I’m not saying that in a pejorative sense — seeing these people walking around like lemmings, obeying without any knowledge base, to put the mask on their face. Social distancing is also useless because COVID is spread by aerosols which travel 30 meters or so before landing. Enclosures have had such terrible unintended consequences. Everywhere should be opened tomorrow as well as was stated in the Great Barrington Declaration that I circulated prior to this meeting. And a word on testing: I do want to emphasize that I’m in the business of testing for COVID. I do want to emphasize that positive test results do not, underlined in neon, mean a clinical infection. It’s simply driving public hysteria and all testing should stop. Unless you’re presenting to the hospital with some respiratory problem. All that should be done is to protect the vulnerable and to give them all in the nursing homes that are under your control, give them all 3,000 to 5,000 international units of vitamin D every day which has been shown to radically reduce the likelihood of Infection. And I would remind you all that using the province’s own statistics, the risk of death under 65 in this province is one in 300,000. One in 300,000. You’ve got to get a grip on this. The scale of the response that you are undertaking with no evidence for it is utterly ridiculous given the consequences of acting in a way that you’re proposing. All kinds of suicides, business closures, funerals, weddings etc. It’s simply outrageous! It’s just another bad flu and you’ve got to get your minds around that. Let people make their own decisions. You should be totally out of the business of medicine. You’re being led down the garden path by the chief medical officer of health for this province. I am absolutely outraged that this has reached this level. It should all stop tomorrow. Thank you very much. Leading Canadian Health Expert Outraged at Government Response to COVID  Dr. Roger Hodkinson, MA, MB, FRCPC, FCAP, CEO and medical director of Western Medical Assessments, spoke at the Edmonton City Council Community and Public Services Committee meeting on Nov. 13 about the city’s move to extend its face-covering bylaw. He was listed as speaker number 95 on the meeting agenda.  Dr. Hodkinson was trained at Cambridge University in the UK. He is ex-president of the pathology section of the Medical Association. He was the chairman of the Royal College of Physicians of Canada Examination Committee and Pathology in Ottawa, Canada.  Here’s the transcript of Hodkinson’s testimony:  This is Dr. Hodkinson, I just wanted to let you know I’m standing by. OK, well we would love to hear from you, the floor is yours. Thank you very much. I do appreciate the opportunity to address you on this very important matter. What I’m going to say is lay language, and blunt. It is counter-narrative, and so you don’t immediately think I’m a quack, I’m going to briefly outline my credentials so that you can understand where I’m coming from in terms of knowledge base in all of this. I’m a medical specialist in pathology which includes virology. I trained at Cambridge University in the UK. I’m the ex-president of the pathology section of the Medical Association. I was previously an assistant professor in the Faculty of Medicine doing a lot of teaching. I was the chairman of the Royal College of Physicians of Canada Examination Committee and Pathology in Ottawa, but more to the point I’m currently the chairman of a biotechnology company in North Carolina selling the COVID-19 test. And [inaudible] you might say I know a little bit about all of this. The bottom line is simply this: There is utterly unfounded public hysteria driven by the media and politicians. It’s outrageous. This is the greatest hoax ever perpetrated on an unsuspecting public. There is absolutely nothing that can be done to contain this virus. Other than protecting older, more vulnerable people. It should be thought of as nothing more than a bad flu season. This is not Ebola. It’s not SARS. It’s politics playing medicine and that’s a very dangerous game. There is no action of any kind needed other than what happened last year when we felt unwell. We stayed home, we took chicken noodle soup, we didn’t visit granny and we decided when we would return to work. We didn’t need anyone to tell us. Masks are utterly useless. There is no evidence base for their effectiveness whatsoever. Paper masks and fabric masks are simply virtue-signaling. They’re not even worn effectively most of the time. It’s utterly ridiculous. Seeing these unfortunate, uneducated people — I’m not saying that in a pejorative sense — seeing these people walking around like lemmings, obeying without any knowledge base, to put the mask on their face. Social distancing is also useless because COVID is spread by aerosols which travel 30 meters or so before landing. Enclosures have had such terrible unintended consequences. Everywhere should be opened tomorrow as well as was stated in the Great Barrington Declaration that I circulated prior to this meeting. And a word on testing: I do want to emphasize that I’m in the business of testing for COVID. I do want to emphasize that positive test results do not, underlined in neon, mean a clinical infection. It’s simply driving public hysteria and all testing should stop. Unless you’re presenting to the hospital with some respiratory problem. All that should be done is to protect the vulnerable and to give them all in the nursing homes that are under your control, give them all 3,000 to 5,000 international units of vitamin D every day which has been shown to radically reduce the likelihood of Infection. And I would remind you all that using the province’s own statistics, the risk of death under 65 in this province is one in 300,000. One in 300,000. You’ve got to get a grip on this. The scale of the response that you are undertaking with no evidence for it is utterly ridiculous given the consequences of acting in a way that you’re proposing. All kinds of suicides, business closures, funerals, weddings etc. It’s simply outrageous! It’s just another bad flu and you’ve got to get your minds around that. Let people make their own decisions. You should be totally out of the business of medicine. You’re being led down the garden path by the chief medical officer of health for this province. I am absolutely outraged that this has reached this level. It should all stop tomorrow. Thank you very much.  Dr Roger Hodkinson on how governments responded to COVID:  https://youtu.be/Hzbz_gL6qEo  https://www.facebook.com/178772728799738/videos/284868239575668/  Dr Roger Hodkinson is the CEO and Medical Director of Western Medical Assessments https://westernmedical.ca/employees/roger-g-hodkinson/  Great Barrington Declaration https://gbdeclaration.org/

COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. (1)  PCR tests cannot detect viral loads and are prone to false positives. (2)  A positive PCR test does not mean that an individual is infected nor infective. (3)  In fact approximately 90% of the PCR positive ‘cases’ are false positives. We therefore have no second wave and no pandemic. (4 , 5)  The government’s report estimates a false positive rate of between 0.8 to 4.0 % using data from other viral infections – not from covid (6)  Viral fragments may remain in people’s bodies for several weeks following recovery from infection. (7)  The crisis will never end if we are waiting for zero positive tests. Everyone has probably had a cold caused by a coronavirus and will likely have a few viral fragments matching those of the cousin SARS-CoV-2 virus (8)  Testing healthy asymptomatic individuals is non-sensical, unscientific and a colossal waste of money.  Antibody testing is not the gold standard as many people have T-cell immunity, and antibodies may not circulate following recovery from infection.  Viral RNA detection by PCR does not equate to infectiousness or viable virus — PCR testings are scientifically meaningless because it is not a diagnostic tool, so why keep testing and testing people?

Sorry for the long post skip if u r bored. Thks. 26th 2020 Feb OA waved to alert me n came to ask if I had anything to tell her. . We talked about the old uncle patient who fell on 24th Feb 2020. OA told the centre was arranging for an escot to take him home after dialysis which he became weak always. Usually I would walk him to the taxi stand whenever I could. Most nurses said they had instructions no need to walk him to the taxi stand if he was feeling tired he just wait. Few would walk him. I was told the nurses asked him to wait till the nurses finished their duties then a nurse would walk him to the taxi stand. Which was not always true. Most importantly on 26th Feb I told the OA a Singaporean to lookout for foreign nurses should they were rude or bully the Singaporean patients. I didn't that was wrong n racist. I cited the incident of a Malaysian Indian senior nurse who I witnessed mimicked the sound of a deaf dying old patient. With actions too. The old uncle patient patient had a feeding tube running thru his nose. When I brought it up I was told by the manager an India Indian she would talk to the Malaysian Indian nurse. What was the outcome I was not told. Until at a meeting facilitated by the Msw officer the CEO was chairing the Malaysian Indian nurse testified that I was giving her problem she was actually playing n treated the dying old uncle patient like a father. What I saw was different with the managers backing her it made me looked bad. She was lying. I told the CEO if she dares to swear what I said was a lie I was willing to stop my dialysis. But at the meeting my only intention was to tell the CEO about the senior nurses taking money n one Pinoy the most senior nurse was not only taking money but wanted to borrow money from an old auntie patient. The Pinoy even dared to ask the old auntie patient to borrow from loanshark for him. I requested to speak to the CEO alone. The Msw officer was told by the CEO to stay. When I brought the matrer of the corrupted Pinoy nurse the CEO was not interested n snubbed me telling he was told by his staff everything he needed to know. The CEO was likely told what the staff wanted him to know. The staff were worried I told all that had happened at the centre. Another important matter was the centre was running at random n many SOPs were not strictly followed. Later another Msw manager from another district came to talk to me. I told him about the centre many medical lapses. The Msw manager said he had informed the nurses no food allowed n no money allowed to received. But food n money were freely given n accepted. These were not what I bothered I was more worry about these foreign nurses taking big money especially the most senior nurse a Pinoy. I was telling the Msw manager many times the Pinoy was really leeching his behavior was out of sorts. The Msw manager told me the Pinoy was considered the position of a centre nurse manager. I remember telling the clinical nurse manager n Msw manager that the Pinoy couldn't be trusted. U didn't elaborate in case 'I beat the bush n scare the snake'. The Msw manager n myself even went to talk to the clinical nurse manager an India Indian weeks before the corrupted Pinoy the most senior nurse at the centre. The manager said the Pinoy had some personal problems not convenient to discuss. The manager was covering up for the Pinoy like she always had for years. That was how the corrupted Pinoy n few of his fellow nurse plied their trade for many years. Weeks later the Pinoy disappeared with patients' money. The manager pretended she didn't know anything she n her superior the district nurse manager were busy telling the victims n Filipino nurses to keep mum about the disappearance of the Pinoy nurse. I was warned by the 2 patients to stop talking about the Pinoy. The rest of the victims didn't tell me anything. The nurses were angry with me if not the managers already talked smothered the victims. The HQ didn't knew about so many patients lent money to the Pinoy only the one that informed HQ  . The Pinoy disappeared around July 2019. I knew 5 lent him money how many more I do not know. With his monthly salary he should be able to pay the 5 victims in not much time but he chose to leave Singapore. I believe there should be many more victims. I already informed the Msw manager about the number of victims I know. N HQ knew too how the Pinoy got to get out of the country was the question. The district nurse manager n clinical nurse manager played a big part smothering the full extent of his doings. In another words the managers helped him to run. If he takes from able n well off I don't care but he took from poor old sick Singaporeans for years he was here. One of the victims who moved about on a motorised scooter. He was about 50 years old. We talked a few times over months about the corrupted pi oy nurse but later stopped talking tell g me the managers told him not to say.. The managers were obstructing the course of justice. His fellow Filipino nurses likely followed what he was doing. I was kicked out for teing the OA the Pinay nurses were taking money from an old auntie patient for wheeling her into the centre. The managers made a police report of harassment to Clementi police station. The IO called me n told me the names of persons who made the report. This is the biggest medical centre of its kind managers n directors r not upright how to run the centres. Will they cover up suspicious death? I believe the managers will. The CEO has to bear the responsibilities. To kicked me out was not the solution only to nursed the hard feelings of the nurses managers n directors n to forcefully closed the ugly matters. . The right thing to do was to discipline the foreign nurses n the managers. The directors were weak handling the juniors staff. Don't they feel ashamed. N I m sore. ' Beggers cannot be choosers' I m recieving free treatments I should not be talking. But as Singaporean I cannot allow these foreign medical workers to be rude n take advantage of our poor sick n old patients. After doing always deny n not embarrass or shy. I don't speak I cannot call myself a Singaporean. .

12月08日 新加坡疫情统计数据报告：新增确诊病例12、累计确诊病例58,332、(包括：累计境外及客工确诊病例55,401、累计社区确诊病例2,884、累计旅客确诊病例47)。累计重症住院病例28(其中累计危重症病例0)、累计死亡病例29、累计确诊轻症隔离病例60、累计治愈病例58,168。死亡率0.04%。 Roylab Stats World Map全球新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例超68,023,745、累计死亡病例超1,552,943。死亡率2.28%。 美国新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例：15,370,339、累计死亡病例：290,474。死亡率1.88%。占全球确诊率：22.59%、占全球死亡率：18.70%。中国排列72、马来西亚排列84、新加坡排列87。 新型冠状肺炎病毒至今发现变异后共有基本六种类型，病毒专家认为可能与地区人种有关，最先采集到病毒样本的是中国湖北武汉研究所，从武汉人民确诊病例采集样本最初定为甲型，后来之前在武汉举行的军人运动会共有一百多个国家参加，美国有五名军人曾因发热到人民医院求诊，五名军人进行体检及病源采样，但还未施于治疗就被美军方强制接走。武汉研究所回顾发现五名军人病毒样本与武汉人民确诊者属同病毒株链型，定性病毒美军人属原始型病毒株链甲型、武汉为乙型、旅欧回国阳性者为丙型。欧洲各国则为丙型及丁型，而在美国有原始的甲型、丙型、戊型，南美洲、印度及非洲除上述类型外偶见巳型者。如今世界卫生组织对以上报道尚未作出结论，由于疫情全球爆发首要任务就是防控为主，将来如何追本溯源还需进行大量的调查寻找可靠的证据链。疫苗的研发有利于抑制病毒广泛性传播感染群体，疫苗开发种类性能有十二类别，基本有效可形成抗体经三期临床实验有效性则只有四种，尚无一种全方位疫苗可抗击不同类型病毒疫苗。 美国莫德纳的COVID-19疫苗有效性94.5%，或许存在5.5%安全性隐患，未达100%临床有效性，莫德纳要求批准本地实施应用接种，医药卫生管理局管控肩负国人生命安全责任重大。医管局鉴定必须采样进行动物实验室研究：检验moderna made in US疫苗实际数据化验报告，分成低剂量组、中剂量组、高剂量组、空白组，每组10只SD小白鼠进行疫苗注射后观察；3天后每组随机抽样体内病毒抗体形成情况，每组2只进行感染观察抗体反应；1周后每组随机抽样体内病毒抗体形成情况，每组2只进行感染观察抗体反应；2、3、4周后每组随机抽样体内病毒抗体形成情况，每组2只进行感染观察抗体反应。动物实验结果报告能否安全应用在人体上，以及产生抗体后能否有效抗击COVID-19病毒的感染达到一定的有效预防作用。鉴定标准及国人生命安全标准存在差异性的有效率P值可比性显著性有别？

Just because I am socially responsible and I am sure no one will download the app if they know the inconvenience and the treatment they have to go through!

Case 58425 is a Short-Term Visit Pass holder who was allowed entry into Singapore to visit his family members who are Singaporeans. He is asymptomatic, and was detected when he went for a COVID-19 pre-departure test on 28 November before a scheduled trip to the US.  He was conveyed to the hospital when his test came back positive for COVID-19 infection on 29 November. His serological test result is also positive, which indicates likely past infection.  He had arrived in Singapore from Nepal on 1 November, and was placed on 14-day SHN at a dedicated facility upon arrival in Singapore from 1 November to 15 November. He was tested negative for COVID-19 infection on 11 November while serving SHN. He subsequently stayed at a friend’s flat at Bishan Street 22, and visited his family staying at Yishun Avenue 6.

So as not to sound like I am pouring cold water on a seemingly good news. As was stated many of the imported cases were without symptoms which means asymptomatic. According to data, as many as 70 pct of people positive were asymptomatic and can remain so without developing symptoms at a later stage. people with symptoms would normally seek treatment in gp or hospital. But asymptomatic do not see a gp or hospital for obvious reason. They do not know they were infected.Those who got tested in gp or hospital then, will come into moh radar and be counted in the data. Therein lies the danger as asymptomatic can be in the community shedding virus as they go and these people goes undetected. So my point is there are lots of asymptomatic in our community. And they are not imported cases and will never be in the data. How did he catch the virus.? It is probably from another asymptomatic.  I understand that MOH daily numbers should not lull us into complacency.  Because one need to analyse objectively to know what is exactly happening in reality. So  put on your mask and social distance until a vaccine is available. Travel bubble is jumping the gun.

If IP plans are to increase their coverage too, to justify their increasing premium. It will result in higher premiums again for those who already had IP plans coverage too. That is a double whammy.  This round of changes is sending the message to pple that they should forego their IP plans and just stick to the basic MediShield life plan provided by the gov. Of course whether private insurers will increase their premiums or not remains unknown. If basic MediShield life is going that direction of increasingly “improving” more coverages as medical and hospitalisation cost continue to increase in the future, it is unwittingly asking pple to terminate and forego their IP plans as gov will go the path of what private insurers are already doing. Such plans will increasingly becoming a burden then to mitigate hospitalisation costs in the future. While some, whom already suffering from chronic diseases may continue with IP coverage, they may no longer care to keep their conditions in check. Cos doing so will mean incurring own medical cost without coverage by MediShield life. While seeing their conditions get worsen and be hospitalised, they do not hv to worry as their hospitalisation coverage is already taken care with their IP plans. Resulting in more claims to further burdening the national healthcare insurance. Already the move to remove “as charged” with co-payment, it had already increased burden on members. I do not see the value anymore with IP plans if members choose the path to keep their chronic diseases in check. This new changes really confirmed that IP plans are not only unnecessary, these are no longer a value coverage seeing the premiums continue to increase. If Sg is truly wishing to see its pple maintain good health.

Ministry of Health, Singapore The problem is that the government reacts too slowly to a changing situation. Earlier in the year, news was already surfacing that there was asymptomatic transmission, yet the government was still bragging that it had learned from SARS, which was purely symptomatic transmission. I was saying then that we were fighting the wrong enemy.  The situation has changed again. If you look at the statistics of many of the countries, you see that the second wave has much higher daily cases than the first wave. Yet, the daily deaths in the second wave are much lower than the first. Something has definitely changed. Nobody is certain what it is. It could be treatment protocols (e.g., lying prone instead of on the back, when to deliver intubation, etc), better medical treatments, more available medical equipment and supplies, or the virus itself may have mutated to become less deadly. Another harsh possibility brought up is that, the moribund cases built up has been cleared: in other words, sadly, the grim reaper has already taken the most vulnerable ones. Many of the cases now are not even clinically sick - they just test positive possibly because of the presence of antibodies or RNA fragments left by the virus much earlier.  Presently we have zero cases locally. The odd local cases that appear are mostly from the dormitories. And the evidence suggests the disease is much less deadly now. Any rational assessment of the situation should conclude that the real threat level now is very low. Yet we remain at DORSCON Orange, contrary to what the DORSCON chart itself prescribes. Yet we are wearing masks and socially distancing against a virus that has largely disappeared among the community. Yet businesses and activities are severely limited, causing unnecessary inconvenience and physical, social, economic and mental suffering to the people. The costs (very real) and benefits (pretty dubious) just don't add up any more.  Perhaps our well paid ministers, whose livelihoods are not affected, who commute maskless in their cars and not take the public transport, who enjoy peaceful walks in their gardens of their landed houses, perhaps they should have more heart for the common people weary from Covid fatigue?

COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. The Flawed PCR Test You might have the virus, but so what? That doesn’t mean you’re sick!  * https://youtu.be/SjyfTvdr1_s Virology is Hoaxology: Viruses do not exist. Period.  Even if you strongly believe in germ theory, there are some serious problems with the generally accepted method of testing for a virus, it’s called the PCR (Polymerase Chain Reaction) test.  The PCR test amplifies a specific region of a DNA strand (the DNA target)—It is qualitative not quantitative; in other words, it can tell you if a virus is present or not, but it can’t tell you in what quantities, and it can’t make any accurate assessment about whether the presence of that virus or not is enough to cause disease.  The US CDC admits that a positive coronavirus COVID-19 test (using the PCR method) doesn’t mean the virus is causing the disease/symptoms you may have.  1. These are the actual words of the US CDC: “Positive [test] results are indicative of active infection with 2019-nCoV but do not rule out bacterial infection or co-infection with other viruses. The agent detected may not be the definite cause of disease.”  2. These are the actual words of the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID) and the Chapter of Infectious Disease Physicians, Academy of Medicine, Singapore, point no.5: https://www.ams.edu.sg/view-pdf.aspx?file=media%5C5558_fi_168.pdf&ofile=Period+of+Infectivity+Position+Statement+%28final%29+23-5-20.pdf Microbiologic Data for Period of Infectivity and Viral RNA Shedding: "It is important to note that viral RNA detection by PCR does not equate to infectiousness or viable virus." The pathogen and the disease it causes are modeled largely on SARS, but it is more transmissible in the community setting by people with mild symptoms.  The disease starts in pig farms in Brazil, quietly and slowly at first, but then it starts to spread more rapidly in healthcare settings. When it starts to spread efficiently from person to person in the low-income, densely packed neighborhoods of some of the megacities in South America, the epidemic explodes. It is first exported by air travel to Portugal, the United States, and China and then to many other countries. Although at first some countries are able to control it, it continues to spread and be reintroduced, and eventually no country can maintain control.  There is no possibility of a vaccine being available in the first year. There is a fictional antiviral drug that can help the sick but not significantly limit spread of the disease.  Since the whole human population is susceptible, during the initial months of the pandemic, the cumulative number of cases increases exponentially, doubling every week. And as the cases and deaths accumulate, the economic and societal consequences become increasingly severe.  The scenario ends at the 18-month point, with 65 million deaths. The pandemic is beginning to slow due to the decreasing number of susceptible people. The pandemic will continue at some rate until there is an effective vaccine or until 80-90 % of the global population has been exposed. From that point on, it is likely to be an endemic childhood disease.

HIGH INFECTIVITY WITH LOW MORTALITY IS GOOD NEWS  •••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••  UNDERSTANDING HOW OUR IMMUNE SYSTEM OPERATE Everyone’s immune system is different but, as a general rule, as we expose to more pathogens, we develop more immunity.  Once an antibody has been produced, a copy remains in the body so that if the same antigen appears again, it can fight off more quickly.  That is why with some diseases, such as chickenpox, you only get it once as the body has a chickenpox antibody stored, ready and waiting to destroy it next time it arrives.  This is called immunity.  There are three types of immunity in humans called innate, adaptive, and passive:  Innate immunity: We are all born with some level of immunity to invaders. Human immune systems, similarly to those of many animals, will attack foreign invaders from day one. This innate immunity includes the external barriers of our body—the first line of defense against pathogens—such as the skin and mucous membranes of the throat and gut. This response is more general and non-specific. If the pathogen manages to dodge the innate immune system, adaptive or acquired immunity kicks in.  Adaptive (acquired) immunity: This protect from pathogens develops as we go through life. As we are exposed to diseases or get vaccinated, we build up a library of antibodies to different pathogens. This is sometimes referred to as immunological memory because our immune system remembers previous enemies.  Passive immunity: This type of immunity is “borrowed” from another source, but it does not last indefinitely. For instance, a baby receives antibodies from the mother through the placenta before birth and in breast milk following birth. This passive immunity protects the baby from some infections during the early years of their life.  SUMMARY The immune system is incredibly complicated and utterly vital for our survival. Several different systems and cell types work in perfect synchrony (most of the time) throughout the body to fight off pathogens and clear up dead cells.  •••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••  PROVEN EPIDEMIOLOGICAL AND SCIENTIFIC APPROACH TO PANDEMICS Getting everyone infected during a virus outbreak to build immunity towards the virus—with special attention given to the vulnerable group—is the proven epidemiological and scientific model approach. Once an antibody has been produced, a copy remains in the body so that if the same antigen appears again, it can fight off more quickly.  That is why with some diseases, such as chickenpox, you only get it once as the body has a chickenpox antibody stored, ready and waiting to destroy it next time it arrives.  This is called immunity.  There are three types of immunity in humans called innate, adaptive, and passive:  Innate immunity: We are all born with some level of immunity to invaders. Human immune systems, similarly to those of many animals, will attack foreign invaders from day one. This innate immunity includes the external barriers of our body—the first line of defense against pathogens—such as the skin and mucous membranes of the throat and gut. This response is more general and non-specific. If the pathogen manages to dodge the innate immune system, adaptive or acquired immunity kicks in.  Adaptive (acquired) immunity: This protect from pathogens develops as we go through life. As we are exposed to diseases or get vaccinated, we build up a library of antibodies to different pathogens. This is sometimes referred to as immunological memory because our immune system remembers previous enemies.  Passive immunity: This type of immunity is “borrowed” from another source, but it does not last indefinitely. For instance, a baby receives antibodies from the mother through the placenta before birth and in breast milk following birth. This passive immunity protects the baby from some infections during the early years of their life.  SUMMARY The immune system is incredibly complicated and utterly vital for our survival. There are several reasons why Covid-19 is particularly harmful to smokers:  - Smokers may already have chronic lung disease, placing them in the “vulnerable” group, which would greatly increase the risk of serious illness. - Many smokers already have damaged lungs, which reduces the organs’ ability to fight off the coronavirus that causes Covid-19. - Smoking also affects the immune response. - The act of smoking means that fingers (and possibly contaminated cigarettes or delivery systems for new tobacco products) are in contact with lips, which increases the possibility of transmission of the virus from hand to mouth. - Smokers usually take off or adjust their masks to smoke, another opportunity for virus transfer. - Smoking products such as water pipes often involve the sharing of mouth pieces and hoses, which could facilitate the transmission of Covid-19 in communal and social settings. - The virus is breathed out, so it is also possible that the clouds of smoke and vape emitted by the smoker would spread the virus, as these may be forcibly exhaled and therefore travel further than a quiet breath behind a mask.  https://www.scmp.com/print/comment/letters/article/3079006/coronavirus-risks-send-out-yet-another-reminder-smokers-quit-now

The FW Dorm cases is an unlucky hit and the numbers are expected to be high which adds on to the overall tally of SG cases. However it shows how, when someone who may be asymptomatic/defiant of their illness, when in close contact with another for a certain duration, can and will pass the virus on. Hence the reason why social distancing is so important, which eventually led to compulsory wearing of masks. Most of the local community cases, are based on a cluster, be it a meeting, gathering, party, family home, of which, has a high potential of passing the virus on to another. Though there may have been some who got it from unknown sources, majority were in close contact for a duration of time. The measures put out by the Task Force, concentrates on mitigating this primary area of risk. Now with enforcement, it slowly brings the numbers down. However it shouldn't come to such enforcement's if social distancing, something which was emphasized upon early, was adhered to. Thankfully, many Singaporeans have followed and unselfishly made sacrifices during this period. FW Dorms are locked in and may increase in numbers these next few days, but will taper off eventually. Local community cases are important as the need to establish no further cases, will allow much of the restrictions to be lifted. We are getting there and lets not worry about numbers. The objective is to starve the Virus from infecting others.
It is just dark clouds are blocking the sky temporarily and we shall see clear sky again in due course. Cheers to everyone.

I propose for the Ministry of Healthy and relevant agencies to impose a shutdown of food delivery platforms such as Grab, FoodPanda, Deliveroo etc, to prevent new clusters of Covid-19 transmission and the spread of the virus.  It has been evident in the past two weeks of 'Circuit Breaker' that delivery riders have faced tremendous pressure in their job of delivering F&B to customers at home. Shortly after the announcement of tightening and restriction of what is deemed to be “essential”, a number of videos have circulated on the internet which displayed the rowdy behaviour of delivery riders and F&B workers. Some of the commotion between the riders and stores resulted in close contact of these persons in their individual bids to put their point across.  Such behaviour is fairly understandable- likely due to the pressures of increased orders and lacklustre management of orders. These delivery riders on the ground are helpless except to do their utmost to fulfil their daily orders. The delivery platforms have also been purported to be almost impossible for delivery riders to cancel orders in view of unforeseen circumstances such as long waiting times or out-of-stock items. These inadvertently culminate into displays of frustrations, jostling, and hurling of insults or abuses. It has also been evident many F&B locations are ironically, the ground of close gathering of delivery riders who have almost no option to practice safe-distancing at these crowded venues. The mood of Singaporeans from all walks of life is expected to run high through the Circuit Breaker period, and occurences of these disputes are most likely to increase.  One cannot be certain that all delivery riders or F&B outlets are Covid-free. It would take just one infected individual in the nucleus to spread devastating consequences deep into the homes of families waiting for their orders. The measures at wet markets and supermarkets are quite effective in allowing families to purchase groceries. Food establishments also remain open and people should have little difficulty to get food and drinks for consumption. It is timely that the Ministry consider a shutdown of the delivery platforms to minimise potential outbreak of the virus within the community.

When you get a flu vaccine, you have two options:  1. Inactivated influenza vaccines contain flu viruses that have been killed so they can’t cause the flu.  2. Live influenza vaccine (LAIV or FluMist) nasal spray contains a live, but weakened form of the virus.  Here are some of the ingredients you’ll find in the flu vaccine:  Egg protein Many flu vaccines are made by growing the viruses inside fertilised chicken eggs. This means that they contain a small amount of egg protein. A newer version of the vaccine, called Flucelvax, is grown in animal cells instead.  Preservatives Vaccine manufacturers add the preservative thimerosal to multidose vaccine vials. Thimerosal prevents dangerous bacteria and fungi from getting into the vial with each use. Thimerosal contains mercury, which can be toxic in large doses. There isn’t enough evidence to show the small amount contained in the flu vaccine is dangerous. But if you’re concerned, thimerosal-free versions of the flu vaccine are available.  Stabilisers Sucrose, sorbitol, and monosodium glutamate (MSG) are used to keep vaccines stable. They prevent vaccines from losing potency, even when exposed to heat and light. Sucrose is the same table sugar you spoon into coffee and sprinkle on berries. Sorbitol is an artificial sweetener that’s also found in chewing gum. MSG is a flavor enhancer. Commonly thought of as an additive in Chinese food, it’s used in many processed foods. Though certain people are sensitive to MSG, the amount found in the flu vaccine is very small.  Antibiotics Neomycin, gentamicin, and other antibiotics are added to vaccines in very small amounts. They stop bacteria from contaminating the vaccine.  Polysorbate 80 This emulsifier prevents sauces and salad dressings from separating. In vaccines, polysorbate 80 keeps all the ingredients evenly distributed. Though large doses can cause some people to have reactions, the amount in the flu vaccine is very small.  Formaldehyde This natural compound is found in household products from glues and other adhesives to pressed-wood furniture. Formaldehyde is a gas that is soluble in water. It’s used in the flu vaccine to inactivate influenza virus. Routine exposure to large doses of formaldehyde is linked to eye and throat irritation, breathing trouble, and a higher risk for certain cancers. Ministry of Health, Singapore  It’s a good idea to extend the CB measures and more important to close more workplaces especially in any companies where there were staff who had tested positive for  covid-19 cases and yet still continue to operate because they are essential services. So this is where you have look into first.    I hope many of the essential services that are allowed to continue operations should be also revised and reviewed and we should further cut back on movements.   For a start , there are so many essential services concentrated in Changi Airport and as a result a lot of staff movement which includes a significant number of work permit holders. So this is one area where we can scale down as airline frequency is quite Low. Can we consider having Changi airport to close for one month so that we also carry out necessary renovations and upgrade. Also it would enable the airport terminals to go for a complete deep cleaning. This is the best time to speed up any infrastructure upgrades when there is no pax movement .   Any flights in the meantime can be operated from Seletar airport if possible.  So we can still have freighter cargo flights operating.   We need to consider cutting down on essential services movement as much as possible. Let’s all hope our efforts bear positive results soon. Thank you sir.  #sgunited

Thank you Singapore PM,  MOM and MOH🙏  #PM Mr.Lee Hsien Loong # MOM # MOH  Bangladesh High Commission, Singapore  প্রিয় সিঙ্গাপুরের- প্রধানমন্ত্রী,  আমার বাংলাদেশী রুমের সাথী এবং বন্ধুদের পক্ষ থেকে আমরা পক্ষে থেকে সিঙ্গাপুরের সরকারী কর্তৃপক্ষের কাছে আমাদের প্রশংসা নিবন্ধভুক্ত করেছি, তারা  আমাদেরকে তাদের পরিবারের সদস্যদের মতো আচরণ করে, তারা আমাদের দেখিয়েছে যে মানবতা, কীভাবে একে অপরের প্রতি আচরণ করতে হয়।  একজন শ্রমিক হিসাবে আমরা এই দেশে থাকতে পেরে আমরা খুব খুশি।  দেশটি কোবিন -১৯ পরিস্থিতির মুখোমুখি হয়েছে এবং সরকার আমাদেরকে যে সুবিধা দিয়েছে,আমরা খুব খুশি।   ১. দৈনিক ভিত্তিতে আমাদের শীর্ষ মানের খাবার সরবরাহ করেন।   ২. আমাদের জন্য শীর্ষ শ্রেণির মেডিকেল 🏥 পরিষেবা সরবরাহ করেন।   ৩. আমাদের দেহের তাপমাত্রা পরীক্ষা করতে তাপমাত্রা মাপার যন্ত্ব সরবরাহ করেন এবং প্রতিদিন আমাদের প্রতিক্রিয়াটি কীভাবে অনুভূত হয় তা তাদের জানাতে হয়|   ৪) আমারা ভাল না থাকলে আমাদের ক্লিনিক বা হাসপাতালে ভর্তি করে।   5.আমদেরকে আমদের মাসিক বেতন প্রদান করেন |   6 .আরও অনেক আছে।   কোভিন-১৯ পরিস্থিতিটিতে আমরা সিঙ্গাপুরে অংশে এসে আমরা সত্যিই খুব খুশি।  আমাদের এমন অনুভূতি যে আমরা আমাদের মাতৃভূমিতে অবস্থান করছি।   আমারা বেশিরভাগ লোকএখানে প্রায় ১০ থেকে ১৫ বছর কাজ কর আসতেছি, আমাদের নিয়োগকর্তা এবং সিঙ্গাপুর সরকারের কাছ থেকে আমরা যে পরিমাণ ভালবাসা পেয়েছি, তার সত্যই আমরা প্রশংসা করেছি যে আমরা আমাদের সারাজীবন এ সব ভুলতে পারিবো না।   আমরা প্রার্থনা করছি 🙏  সিঙ্গাপুর কোভিন-১৯ যত তাড়াতাড়ি সম্ভব ভাল হয়ে যাক।  যাতে আমরা আবার ঘুরে দেখতে পারি সিঙ্গাপুরেরর আকর্ষণীয় অঞ্চলগুলি আমাদের বন্ধুদের সাথে।   সমস্ত বাংলাদেশী সহকর্মী এবং বন্ধুদের কে আমার পরামর্শ আপনি যদি হোম কোয়ারেন্টাইন ই  থাকেন তা হলে আপনার রুমে আবস্তান করুন এবং আপনার ব্যক্তিগত স্বাস্থ্যবিধি যত্ন নিতে থাকেন, তবে আমরা অন্যের দিকে নজর রাখতে পারবো এবং এই মর্মানতিক মুহুর্তগুলি  পেয়ে কনে আবার একসাথে কাজ করব।   ধন্যবাদ সিঙ্গাপুরের প্রধানমন্ত্রী,  MOM এবং MOH.

WHAT IS IN A FLU VACCINE ? •••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••  When you get a flu vaccine, you have two options:  1. Inactivated influenza vaccines contain flu viruses that have been killed so they can’t cause the flu.  2. Live influenza vaccine (LAIV or FluMist) nasal spray contains a live, but weakened form of the virus.  Here are some of the ingredients you’ll find in the flu vaccine:  Egg protein Many flu vaccines are made by growing the viruses inside fertilised chicken eggs. This means that they contain a small amount of egg protein. A newer version of the vaccine, called Flucelvax, is grown in animal cells instead.  Preservatives Vaccine manufacturers add the preservative thimerosal to multidose vaccine vials. Thimerosal prevents dangerous bacteria and fungi from getting into the vial with each use. Thimerosal contains mercury, which can be toxic in large doses. There isn’t enough evidence to show the small amount contained in the flu vaccine is dangerous. But if you’re concerned, thimerosal-free versions of the flu vaccine are available.  Stabilisers Sucrose, sorbitol, and monosodium glutamate (MSG) are used to keep vaccines stable. They prevent vaccines from losing potency, even when exposed to heat and light. Sucrose is the same table sugar you spoon into coffee and sprinkle on berries. Sorbitol is an artificial sweetener that’s also found in chewing gum. MSG is a flavor enhancer. Commonly thought of as an additive in Chinese food, it’s used in many processed foods. Though certain people are sensitive to MSG, the amount found in the flu vaccine is very small.  Antibiotics Neomycin, gentamicin, and other antibiotics are added to vaccines in very small amounts. They stop bacteria from contaminating the vaccine.  Polysorbate 80 This emulsifier prevents sauces and salad dressings from separating. In vaccines, polysorbate 80 keeps all the ingredients evenly distributed. Though large doses can cause some people to have reactions, the amount in the flu vaccine is very small.  Formaldehyde This natural compound is found in household products from glues and other adhesives to pressed-wood furniture. Formaldehyde is a gas that is soluble in water. It’s used in the flu vaccine to inactivate influenza virus. Routine exposure to large doses of formaldehyde is linked to eye and throat irritation, breathing trouble, and a higher risk for certain cancers. There are only four ways to stop the virus (and many other viruses): 1) quarantine or lock everyone within our borders at home for 2 months (Wuhan), except for food and essential services. Govt teach people how to make a washable cloth mask with a filter/tissue pocket. The tissue can be changed anytime, and the mask can be washed.  3) social distancing. Ineffective when community spread is high. Troublesome and hard to control. Flattens curve but still economically costly, results uncertain, extra budgets to support businesses, unemployed etc. 4) herd immunity.   Over 90% of positive cases came from asymptomatic or presymptomatic transmissions. Nobody in their right mind would want to walk next to a sick person, and a sick person would not intentionally spread it.  The remaining 10% are those in health care environments.   Therefore, wearing masks will stop the asymptomatic and presymptomatic carriers from spreading the virus.

My two cents worth…  If we may have noticed, there are 3 keywords frequently appeared around the world with regards to COVID-19, they are: 1. Imported 2. Linked 3. Unlinked  So what should be done in Singapore to prevent further increase of the infected numbers? I personally think that there are a few measures need to take seriously in the current context.  1. Imported cases has increased tremendously, this is inevitable considering Singapore a small red dot in Asia, where many people have to travel around the world to make a living, regardless of their nationality and occupation. We have businessmen traveling across the global to sign deals, professionals providing their expertise globally in various trades, students studying aboard, home helpers and foreign skilled workers that facilitated the growth of Singapore etc. Yes, the government has kicked in preventive measures to make sure the possibility of spreading the virus contained. But have all these measures been taken seriously by the people going into Singapore? Unfortunately to some people, social responsibility is not what they really care about. To tackle this, my suggestion is to step up the cost of not abide to the rules. Increase manpower to monitor their whereabout and conditions, monitoring should also include their family members that live together. Deploy NS men or neighborhood policemen to spot check them daily, track the movement of their family members.  2. Except family members living together, everyone should not go out unnecessarily. Tracking and monitoring of those just returned, their family members and those linked to previous cases are crucial. As mentioned earlier, stepping up stringent measures for Stay Home Notice, frequent house visit is a MUST, as the cost of relying on human consciousness is too high. People not serving Stay Home Notice but under tracking and monitoring due to their linkage should put up mask when going out, this is to ensure virus not spread if the person suddenly infected. Furthermore, this is so much better of having the whole nation putting up mask.  3. No more gatherings should be allowed regardless of the number of people involved and their religion, this is to break the link of spreading the virus. Nobody can tell whether the person passes by is infected or not, you can’t take the risk of giving them the benefit of the doubt that everyone has the integrity and conscious about social responsibility. Of course, in some cases those infected they themselves not knowing as well. Hence, instead of looking for cure why not prevent it from happening in the first place? Unlinked means not knowing where the virus came from, no previous record or trace of how the person became infected. So beside no gathering, stay out when necessarily, like buying food (pack food back to eat instead of eating out) and daily necessities, go to work (also pack back to eat during lunch or dinner) and go to school. Conduct business meetings using the internet, work from home if can, cook at home if can too. Everyone should limit their movement so as to contain the risk of been infected and spreading the virus.  In the current situation, we might have to forgo a bit of democracy and humanitarianism, just to ensure that Singapore is a safe, healthy and clean nation to live in. These are the fundamentals of a sustainable Singapore.

I'm no app developer but as a user this app is of little use to me.   First, it's good to know that our data would not be accessed unless we were near a confirmed case. But the app itself has a fatal flaw. It has to be kept open always.  Huh? Meaning if I am using Facebook now it would be rendered useless? And I need to keep it face down as a iPhone user so it can continue accessing my location - which means the question isn't on how the battery usage will not only increase but how much the battery usage will be increased. If the mobile phone runs out of juice - again, how effective is this in active tracing?  Another question would be on security. What is being done to ensure the app is safe to use - since Bluetooth signal is kept on constantly with the app running in foreground seems like a good and simple way for someone with knowledge in the field to tap on and gain access to our data from our phones - not from your database.  Lastly, with Covid-19 affecting elderly the most; shouldn't the app be all the more made user friendly for them? Please do consider offering them in other languages like Mandarin, Malayu and Tamil. Maybe not all, but there are many elderly who knows how to operate a smartphone but not all of these elderly understand English.  If you have a pop-up to alert users who have been near a confirmed case it would be even better since now I understood that the user would be contacted via phone only.  I appreciate the gesture and think this is a great concept but the way it's implemented is not very assuring.

More testing can pick up and isolate positive cases to prevent community transmission.   "Vò, a town of 3,300 just outside Venice, was part of an experiment that involved aggressive testing and quarantine measures. Every single resident was tested for coronavirus in late February when Northern Italy was first rocked by the outbreak, and 3% of inhabitants were found to be carrying the virus.  Andrea Crisanti, an infections expert at Imperial College London, was involved with the experiment and told news outlets that half of the carriers exhibited no symptoms.  ... “We were able to contain the outbreak here because we identified and eliminated the ‘submerged’ infections and isolated them. That is what makes the difference.”  ... Crisanti also warned Sky News that, "for every patient that shows symptoms for COVID-19 there were about 10 who don't."  Mass asymptomatic testing has also helped South Korea withstand the epidemic without the major city-wide shelter-in-place orders, restaurant closures and travel restrictions being implemented elsewhere."   https://va.news-republic.com/a/6805667350747021830?app_id=1239&gid=6805667350747021830&impr_id=6805708042756360453&language=en&region=us&user_id=6712284013404603398&fbclid=IwAR1gW_90L9LIxDyhC0DXiQYSuXp4kITbKpbeO0SSHFcT3ff4VukU8HHOI5s

With stricter border controls in place, we are down to ensuring personal hygiene and social distancing.  I am very concerned that people here are failing miserably in personal hygiene. If we go by NHS's powerful messaging of "Catch it. Bin it. Kill it", we fail on all 3 counts.  People are still coughing/sneezing without covering with a tissue, still spitting phlegm into tissue and throwing into bowls instead of trash bins (just saw last Sat), and not washing hands before eating (7 adults and kids I observed in a cafe yesterday).  Re: Open-mouthed coughers  8days.sg reader A. Wong told us: I was queuing to pay for (uncovered) breads on a tray at BreadTalk when the lady in front of me turned back and coughed. It was my turn next and so the cashier rung up my order. The lady who coughed wasn’t masked — I was shocked. Coincidentally, she did not ‘infect’ her purchases but instead aimed her cough behind her [at me] — no social responsibility. I later binned the bread for peace of mind. My family and friends told me I shouldn't have paid for it and should have gotten new ones, but everything took place in a short span of time and in hindsight, it might have been for the best so that the possibly germy bread wouldn’t make its way back to the shelf.  https://www.8days.sg/eatanddrink/newsandopening/hey-auntie-quit-tailgating-me-while-queuing-for-kueh-in-the-time-12542414  More impactful messaging and reminders must be used to ensure better personal hygiene.  "One of the most effective ways of protecting everyone is by remember the simple phrase: Catch it. Bin it. Kill it.  CATCH IT – Always carry tissues and use them to cover your nose and mouth when you cough or sneeze.  BIN IT – Dispose of used tissues as soon as possible.  KILL IT – Clean your hands with soap and water as soon as you can and make sure you wash them frequently. If you have no washing facilities, make use of an alcohol gel."  https://wmas.nhs.uk/2013/12/18/remember-to-catch-it-bin-it-kill-it-this-winter/?fbclid=IwAR2P-ZwiVwDdIdE_oOBLoCI6NzODi-v-KJA298Ac8Wxp-lcMYPdLKNJpBw8

KILL IT – Clean your hands with soap and water as soon as you can and make sure you wash them frequently. Dear MOH,  In this time of community care for Singaporeans and PRs, it is time to implement co-payment for foreigners who are on work passes to discourage them from crossing over from other countries with the specific aim of seeking free COVID-19 treatments in Singapore. Currently, all work pass holders in Singapore receive free COVID-19 treatment.   Alternatively, we may want to implement a full payment system for COVID-19 treatment for any foreigners regardless of whether they are work pass holders or not who import the COVID-19 to Singapore from this point onwards.  Some work pass holders are infected with the COVID-19 and returned to Singapore for free COVID-19 treatment. Thank you.

It’s so important that we have knowledge about Coronavirus that we are all battling now. Please read!  Hi guys. As a Chinese, I'd like to share some personal views on the Coronavirus.  I often feel speechless when I watch some international news and comments on social media. It feels like some people don't care about the possibility of a virus outbreak in their own country. And when you tell them about epidemic preventions and their effectiveness in China, someones just yell out that China is lying, and then go on to party without masks.  It's frustrating. The local government of Wuhan made lots of mistakes in the early days, and that led to today's total confirmed case number of more than 80,000. And we have lost at least 3,000 people! Now many countries are making the same mistakes just like they never get information from China. Sometimes I really don't know why????  👉🏻Some say that no symptoms no need for masks, and even discriminate against people who wear masks.  ‼️This virus has a very unpredictable incubation period, and you can infect many people without any symptoms! In one case, a woman infected 7 people even though she did not has any symptoms.   👉🏻Some say that people with mild symptoms can self-heal simply by being isolated at home. And youngs will not die. ‼️That's what we thought at first, but in the end, China had to quickly build specialist hospitals to place and treat *ALL* suspected and confirmed cases to avoid more cross-infection. Without symptomatic treatment, home isolation may turn a mild patient into a serious one. And home-isolated patients may high probably infect their whole family. You may self-heal, what about your parents and children?  BTW, we got some cured cases who are more than 70 when some patients who were only 30 dead. Young doesn't mean healthy or cannot die.  👉🏻Some say that the mortality rate of this disease is very low.  ‼️As mentioned above, the virus is highly contagious and can cause systemic organ failure. The low mortality rate depends on preventing mild cases from developing into severe ones. It depends, in another word, on whether the average medical resource is sufficient. No matter how advanced your country's medical technologies are, they are useless if you cannot get them. Most dead cases of Wuhan was actually due to the early collapse of medical resources at the start. (Just picture all the people rush into the same hospital in one day.)  👉🏻Some believe the virus originated in China and could be prevented by expelling the Chinese.  ‼️What a stupid logic! Aside from the fact that scientists still haven't found the source of the virus (did the Spanish flu originate in Spain?), the most important thing is that to only discriminate against people from one region will let down the guard against patients from other regions. Viruses don't pick nationality or race. Looking at the confirmed cases in Europe, how many of them have clear contacts with China? What's the use of running from an Asian but hugging an infected Italian?  ‼️China's preventive measures include blocking affected areas, keeping residents staying home as far as possible, working and teaching online, organizing large-scale disinfection, and setting up special hospitals, free treatment, calling in medical personnel from all over the country to support Wuhan... Even so, the virus has only reduced its transmission speed and has not been eliminated yet.  (Update: I un-capitalized the word "free" since someone was unhappy about that. Free treatment is important, if infected people can not afford it, they may get sicker and infect more people. It's not a wellness but a precaution. I list these measures here because they exist, not because I want to flaunt them. I haven't left my house for two months. It's not something to be happy or proud about. 😒)  And some countries that have seen a rise in confirmed cases are still debating whether to wear masks, and some internet users are busily laughing at how dirty China is! OMG, is H1N1 showed up cause Mexico or America was too dirty?   People are dealing with a virus together, and some people just wanna be racism. What's packed in their heads?  Anyway, at least trying some preventions which have been proven useful in China to protect people is better than creaming 'China is lying'.   To be frankly I don't care whether people believe thoses suggestions or not. If China lie, the Chinese will pay for it. If other countries don't take enough effective precautions, their citizens will pay for it. If repeating the spell 'lying' can take the virus down, I encourage everyone saying it a thousand times a day.   --But the bad news is it doesn't work! Just wake up and wash your hands guys! Dear reader, we should not miss the golden hours of viral respiratory tract infections (including Corona).   That is the time of earliest symptoms like fatigue, headache, sneezing, nasal block or runny nose, sore palate or throat or feeling unwell.   Don’t delay steam inhalation, warm water face wash and warm water gargling (triple therapy) at this point.   The consequences of not doing steam may be weeks long suffering with fever, severe body aches, loss of appetite, bad coughs (pneumonias), lost hours at work or earnings, waste of money and time for treatments.   If you do steam on time, you may also help to prevent world’s leading cause of antibiotic misuse and overuse.  Steam inhalation not only control your infection early but also helps to reduce the spread it to your loved family and friends.  To watch how to do steam inhalation (triple therapy) effectively please view below YouTube video.  https://youtu.be/JJfeLx22BnE  Jay De Alwis (MBBS)
