Smokers at increased risk of coronavirus complications, leading experts warn Experts say higher death rates among men could be linked to smoking  "High rates of smoking have also been linked to more serious outcomes in both Sars and Mers.  One of the UK’s leading respiratory disease experts, Gisli Jenkins, professor of experimental medicine at Nottingham University, said that smokers had high rates of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), a form of lung damage. And people with COPD are at high risk generally of respiratory illnesses such as the new coronavirus.  Prof Jenkins said it would be “astonishing” if smokers were not at greater risk of Covid-19 than non smokers. And he said there may be a link between high smoking rates and severity of the disease.   “China has extremely high rates of COPD and it also has high rates of severe pneumonia. In this particular coronavirus 15 per cent of the Chinese population who have been infected have severe respiratory disease and around two per cent have died - in the rest of the world the disease doesn’t seem to be as bad."  https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-dangerous-smokers/

Dear Reader, in my opinion right now all the COVID-19 contact patients all over the world should be doing steam inhalation, warm water face wash and warm water gargling at the earliest cold and flu symptom while waiting for or getting medical treatment. All health care workers who treats such patients should be doing the same as a preventive measure at least twice daily.  I strongly believe currently spreading COVID-19 can be controlled at very early stages with "triple heat therapy" with steam and warm water if performed efficiently.   There is nothing to lose by testing this treatment on early symptomatic new corona viral infected patients. This therapy helps to control the infection by giving time to our immune system while keeping virus growth suppressed. In medical terms this may give natural "live attenuated vaccine" type effect by suppressing the infection with "Cell mediated immunity" till full control taken over by "Humoral immunity" with producing definite antibodies.  This way of assisting the immune system is way more efficient than let the virus to take over your body, let you suffer to the maximum if not die then gradually allow body to get full antibody effect over couple or more weeks.  I am a medical graduate who is practicing steam and warm water for early control of acute viral respiratory tract infection on myself for 20 years with lot of success. For the past 20 years I have self-treated all my common colds and flues by 48hrs if not within 24hrs. Also controlled two probable influenza events within 72hrs in the winter.   For the past 20 years never had to clear my nose from respiratory secretions, never let it infect lungs with long suffering coughs. Never had antibiotics for sinusitis or lung infections. Never used expectorants. Never been away from work due to any related issues. What else you expect from a treatment which is cheap and simple like this?   I have done a scientific discussion on the possibilities of COVID-19 control through this method.   Please view my video upload through below link.   https://youtu.be/Dom2Oungw7I   End note: I don’t a see a reason to die in thousands and get sick in tens of thousands from a respiratory infection when you have simple, cheap and readily available method of early treatment.  Jay De Alwis (MBBS)

Ministry of Health, Singapore  I was at Bedok Polyclinic a few days ago. The staff have started measuring temperature of everyone entering the polyclinic. A staff used a forehead thermometer while another used an ear thermometer. One must insert the ear thermometer properly into the ear in order to do an accurate reading. In addition, it takes longer for the staff to measure someone’s temperature using the ear thermometer, compared to a forehead thermometer. I would suggest the Polyclinic provides forehead thermometer to their staff instead of the ear thermometer so that they don’t have to come into too close contact with visitors and patients.   Next, it’s regarding water supply in the toilet inside the Bedok Polyclinic. In one of toilets, the water from the taps at the basins were flowing out so little and cut off so fast that it has become so difficult to do a proper hand washing. I am not sure if the same happens in the other toilets in Bedok Polyclinic, or even in other polyclinics. Is this done to cut cost? I think, the polyclinics should provide an environment to facilitate the public into practicing proper hygiene measures, especially in the current time of an epidemic event.   Hope the relevant authority will look into the matters so that  the staff in the polyclinics, together with the public, can protect themselves better in face of this COVID19 epidemic.

Dear Reader, in my opinion right now in Wuhan everyone should be doing steam inhalation, warm water face wash and warm water gargling at the earliest cold and flu symptom while waiting for medical treatment. All health care workers should be doing the same as a preventive measure at least twice daily.  I strongly believe currently spreading COVID-19 can be controlled at very early stages with "triple heat therapy" with steam and warm water if performed efficiently.   There is nothing to lose by testing this treatment on early symptomatic New Corona Viral infection patients. This therapy helps to control the infection by giving time to our immune system while keeping virus growth suppressed. In medical terms this may give natural "live attenuated vaccine" type effect by suppressing the infection with "Cell mediated immunity" till full control taken over by "Humoral immunity" with producing definite antibodies.  I am a medical graduate who is practicing steam and warm water for early control of acute viral respiratory tract infection on myself for 20 years with lot of success. For the past 20 years I have self-treated all my common colds and flues by 48hrs if not within 24hrs. Also controlled two probable influenza events within 72hrs in the winter.   For the past 20 years never had to clear my nose from respiratory secretions, never let it infect lungs with long suffering coughs. Never had antibiotics for sinusitis or lung infections. Never used expectorants. Never been away from work due to any related issues. What else you expect from a treatment which is cheap and simple like this?   I have done a scientific discussion on the possibilities of COVID-19 control through this method.   Please view my video upload through below link.   https://youtu.be/Dom2Oungw7I   Jay De Alwis (MBBS)

This probably can explain why so many cities in China are taking very strict measure and implementing hard/soft lock-down, despite the big impact on economy. Zhejiang province has more than 1000 cases with 0 death, but most cities including Hangzhou are in soft lock-down. The recent cases are already showing the coronavirus is already spreading within the community. As such, we have a few proposals for the MOH to consider to manage local community spreading: 1. All students to stay at home and attend web class. Children do not create economic value now but they are the future of the country, and they should be protected because they cannot protect themselves. They are clustered together every day in school and are generally weaker in immunity and is a high risk group. If a child is inflected, and if the family has an elder, the elderly will also risk been affected. Many cases in China are cluster and family infections which is why China has already banned schools from resuming. If the cases spread to the schools in Singapore it will consume huge amount of our limited medical resources. 2. The government should encourage working from home. I understand the government current reluctance to make more concrete measures may be due to concerns about the impact to the economy. However, this non actions or slow reactions will only cause greater spreads which will end up creating more damage to the economy. I would encourage the government to encourage business to tell their staff to work from home, especially for back office functions. My husband returned from his HK employer. His HK employer, like many other companies in HK, is already asking staff to work from home. HK’s current infection cases are currently lower than Singapore despite its close proximity to mainland China and it large mainland Chinese population. 3. Set up specialize venue for suspected cases to go to. One of the main causes of the spread in Wuhan during the early stage was the patients are going to public hospitals and clinics, and many doctors and medical staff are not aware of this new virus. Many were dismiss as common flu and asked to go back and rest. In the early stage of the spread, many medical staff in Wuhan were down with the virus because they have not taken precaution. Many have only basic face mask. They were not provided protective suits. These staff then spread to their family members and those they were in contact with. In Singapore, our GP and clinics are firstly not equipped to confirm the virus, and secondly their staff are not adequately protected, such that clinics can become a source of the virus if patients continue to go to them. These GPs are scattered across the island, in HDB estates and shopping malls. It would be better to install a few temporary specialized examination centers in Singapore where patients can go to check their cases. As Case 19 demonstrates, she went to TTS but was dismissed as not infected after an X-ray was taken until she insisted for a proper check at second visit at SGH. In the case of Case 34, she went to two GPs but were dismissed. She’s not the only one, Case 37 and Case 39 also went to two clinics. It is not in the interests of GPs to confirm a case as it will mean their clinic will have to be thoroughly cleaned, they and their staff quarantined, and their business affected. The hospitals in Singapore currently tasked to accept these cases are also not properly managing the flow. If someone has a fever and cough, and go to these hospital, they are sitting amongst other patients. These patient are in hospital for some medical reasons and are already low on immunity. By setting up specialized examination center across the island, it will avoid spreading to the already weak. The Chinese who were dealing with so many cases has already proven the X-ray is not effective in confirming if a patient has been infected with the coronavirus. Test kits results are also not entirely reliable. The main method in China is CT scan + test kit, with some suspected cases to be quarantined first and have a second CT to confirm. Many clinics in Singapore are not equipped to do the test, so it make even more senses to conduct the examination in specialized centers. 4. Until now, I still do not understand why the government is telling the public not to wear a face mask unless you are sick. How do you know if a sick person is wearing a face mask when he is supposed to? There are sick children who still goes to school despite been told not to, and there are those who are supposed to be under home quarantined and still roaming outside. Medical staff should be made to wear face mask compulsory while at work. Not only them, but professions that will face many people, such as drivers (2 out of 19 local cases are drivers), hawkers, airport staff, supermarket cashiers, should also be made to wear face mask compulsory. This is for their own protection as well as for the sake of others. 5. Discourage large gatherings, close down entertainment centers, cinemas, resorts and casinos. A few hundred Spaniards can destroy the great Aztec civilization and wipe out more than 90% of the Aztec population because the virus they carry are more efficient than guns. Every one patient is linked to a wide net of immediate family members and extended family members, young and old. Singapore is also one of the most densely populated place in the world. Prevention is better than cure.

Thank you Sir for your reassuring address. Let us all Singaporeans stay kind to one another, be calm and be rational.   I do have some concerns and suggestions though.   Could we - in future - ration the sale of masks and sanitizers once there is a confirmed case? Have heard anecdotal accounts of Chinese nationals snapping these up in boxes before the nationwide frenzy. While it is understandable for them to want to do that, can we make sure that it doesn’t lead to a mass frenzy?   While mortality rates are low, this virus is so much more infectious: the overall number of deaths is likely to be far higher. Isn’t that of huge concern to Singapore?  If so, could we cancel mass events? If not, what are concrete reasons?  If not, can there be clearer comms of what exactly are the safety measures to reassure the public? For example, in the case of the Chinese team still performing in the air show, what was being done to make sure they aren’t in incubation stage?  Very clear comms could allay fears and bring about understanding   We are now second in the world, outside of mainland China, with the highest number of infections. Could we have done more, and done more earlier? This could be a valuable lesson for future outbreaks.   Lastly given how the mortality rate is supposedly so low, are there specific reasons for 4 out of 30 patients being in more serious conditions? Again, clear explanations would be really helpful.  Lastly I do know this is a trying period for everyone including you. So please do take care!

Dear sir,   Sorry to bother you during these difficult time due to the Coronavirus outbreak.   I understand that all work pass holders from China are allowed into Singapore after the Chinese New Year break. I understand the need of these workers as I am in the renovation industry.   I fully agree to have these workers on home-quarantine for 14 days upon their return and fully support this measure. But I have 1 concern on top of this move.   It is stated in many mainstream article that those infected or carrying the virus may not have any symptoms of illness. So, is it really safe for these home-quarantined workforce to return to work after 14 days if they do not show any symptoms? What if they are infected but did not show any symptoms?   I believe everyone is thoughtful and do not wish to spread the virus to people around them, especially their love ones. But I think many of those who affected others don't even know they had done so because they don't even know they themselves are infected. Dear Mr Lawrence Wong,  When the government decided to make it compulsory for those returning from China to go on Leave of Absence, did you consider that the majority of these people will be returning to their rented rooms and staying together with their landlords? While not going to work as a precaution to ensure the safety of the general public, landlords and their families are then forced into a situation where they have to be in close proximity to these “suspect” cases 24/7 for 14 days.  These same people will be going to work and going about their daily business as usual.  Does that not contravene the original purpose of your action – which is to safeguard the general public?  Isn’t there a glaring loophole here?  I am a landlord to such a tenant who returned home just yesterday.  And because I am not so unreasonable as to stop her from coming back to my place, I have decided to self-quarantine myself too as I also feel responsible to the general public.  Fortunately, I am self-employed and work from home most of the time and so I can do this.  But I am still inconvenienced as I have to refrain from visiting my elderly mother these two weeks or to meet my son when he books out of BMT for fear he may not be able to book in when he declares this situation to his army superiors.  But what about those landlords and family members who have to go to work?  Wouldn’t it be the same as if the returning Chinese people were not required to go on Leave of Absence at all?  That defeats the purpose of your action in the first place, wouldn’t it?  Last by not least, in this interview here, https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/about-30000-work-pass-holders-from-china-yet-to-return-josephine-teo Mr Shanmugam said and I quote: "You know they are on leave of absence or home quarantine so that the rest of Singapore, all of us, can be saved. So if they are tossed out onto the streets, where are they going to go? We have to avoid these sorts of irrational actions."  Does that mean that the government is making martyrs of us landlords so that “the rest of Singapore, all of us, can be saved”?  WOW – do we landlords get an award for this?

THREE MORE CONFIRMED IMPORTED CASES OF WUHAN CORONAVIRUS INFECTION IN SINGAPORE  30TH JAN 2020                    As of 30 January 2020, 2pm, the Ministry of Health (MOH) has confirmed three additional imported cases of Wuhan coronavirus infection in Singapore. Ten confirmed cases were earlier announced by MOH.  2.               There is currently no evidence of community spread in Singapore.  About the cases  Case 11  3.               The 11th case is a 31 year-old female Chinese national from Wuhan who arrived in Singapore on 22 January. She was a travelling companion of the fourth confirmed case1. She is currently warded in an isolation room at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID).  4.               The case reported that she was asymptomatic during her flight to Singapore. She was identified as a close contact of the fourth confirmed case and had been quarantined from 26 January. She developed symptoms on 27 January, and was admitted to NCID. Subsequent test results confirmed Wuhan coronavirus infection on 29 January at about 11pm.  Case 12  5.               The 12th confirmed case is a 37 year-old female Chinese national from Wuhan who arrived in Singapore with her family on 22 January. She is currently warded in an isolation room at the NCID.  6.               The case reported that she was asymptomatic during her flight to Singapore. She subsequently developed symptoms on 26 January. She took a taxi to Tan Tock Seng Hospital on 29 January, and was classified as a suspect case and immediately isolated at NCID. Subsequent test results confirmed Wuhan coronavirus infection on 29 January at about 11pm.  7.               Prior to hospital admission, the case stayed at Village Hotel Sentosa (10 Artillery Avenue), Hotel 81 Princess (21 Lorong 12 Geylang) and Home Suite View Hotel (12 Lorong 12 Geylang). She indicated that she had visited Orchard Road and Geylang, and had travelled by taxi. The risk of infection from transient contact, such as on public transport or in public places, is assessed to be low.  Case 13  8.               The 13th confirmed case is a 73 year-old female Chinese national who arrived in Singapore from Wuhan with her family on 21 January. She was tested positive for Wuhan coronavirus infection on 30 January at about 2pm. She is currently warded in an isolation room at NCID and her condition is stable.  9.               MOH has initiated epidemiological investigations and contact tracing to identify individuals who had close contact with the cases.  Update on condition of confirmed cases  10.           The three new cases are stable currently, and we are continuing to monitor their health. As for the ten previously announced cases, none is critically ill. All of them remain in stable condition, and most are improving.   Update on suspect cases  11.           As of 30 January, 12pm, 164 of the suspect cases have tested negative for the Wuhan coronavirus, and 13 have tested positive (case 13 was confirmed at about 2pm, 30 January). Test results for the remaining 49 cases are pending.  Update on contact tracing for confirmed cases  12.           Contact tracing for the confirmed cases is ongoing. Once identified, MOH will closely monitor all close contacts. As a precautionary measure, they will be quarantined for 14 days from their last exposure to the patient. In addition, all other identified contacts who have a low risk of being infected will be under active surveillance, and will be contacted daily to monitor their health status.  13.           As of 30 January, 12pm, MOH has identified 170 close contacts. Of the 139 who are still in Singapore, 135 have been contacted and are being quarantined or isolated. Efforts are ongoing to contact the remaining four close contacts.  Health advisory  14.           Singaporeans are advised to defer all travel to Hubei Province and all non-essential travel to Mainland China.  15.           All travellers should monitor their health closely for two weeks upon return to Singapore and seek medical attention promptly if they feel unwell. Travellers should inform their doctor of their travel history. If they have a fever or respiratory symptoms (e.g. cough, shortness of breath), they should wear a mask and call the clinic ahead of the visit.  16.           Travellers and members of the public should adopt the following precautions at all times: ·       Avoid contact with live animals including poultry and birds, and consumption of raw and undercooked meats; ·       Avoid close contact with people who are unwell or showing symptoms of illness; ·       Observe good personal hygiene; ·       Practise frequent hand washing with soap (e.g. before handling food or eating, after going to toilet, or when hands are dirtied by respiratory secretions after coughing or sneezing); ·       Wear a mask if you have respiratory symptoms such as a cough or shortness of breath; ·       Cover your mouth with a tissue paper when coughing or sneezing, and dispose the soiled tissue paper in the rubbish bin immediately; and ·       Seek medical attention promptly if you are feeling unwell.  17.           MOH will continue to monitor the situation closely. As medical practitioners are on the lookout for cases with pneumonia who have recently been in China, Singapore is likely to see more suspect cases that will need to be investigated for possible links to the Wuhan cluster.  ____________ 1  The fourth case is a 36 year-old male Chinese national from Wuhan who arrived in Singapore on 22 January.

Dear Minister of Health  Gan Kim Yong  I write this message as a Singaporean who is gravely concerned for the well being of all Singapore citizens and residents, and who is worried at the style and speed with which your government is acting.  1. First Observation - within a matter of days, Singapore has run out of face masks. None of the pharmacies I visited today have a single piece of mask left. Why is this so? Is it because our supply chain is not robust? Is it because we allowed visitors to buy an indiscriminate number of masks? Are these visitors exporting masks? Are businesses being held accountable or are they diverting the masks to the next most profitable client / country? Is the government doing anything to investigate / verify / and place measures to counteract the above-mentioned points via solid actions? I strongly recommend that the government work to Ensure a strong supply of masks. A suggestion - Restrict Tourists to purchase only 1 piece per passport per day and reserve at least X pieces of mask per Singapore residing household per day, depending on the number of family members. You have all the data. Please Ensure that you remember a fundamental principle: Singaporeans should be entitled to a safe environment and it is your duty to deliver on that entitlement.  2. Second observation - Only today was it released that Hubei residents will be restricted from entering Singapore. 3 questions come to mind - Why only Hubei and not Whole of China? n-COV is more contagious than SARS. Why only today and not within 48 hours of the crisis? Why did we allow approx 2000 China visitors to roam the streets freely? I am sure you and your team of able Ministers had consulted very able and talented Doctors, Professors, International agencies. It is public news days ago that this virus is more virulent and contagious than SARS. Should stronger measures not have been put into place within 24-48H of the virus becoming international news? Have you questioned the speed, efficiency and confidence with which you and your fellow ministers have put in place measures?  Minister, do remember that the health & safety of all Singaporeans is your responsibility.  And it seems to many Singaporeans at this juncture, that this responsibility is not being carried out well. Prove us wrong. Just ask yourself if we want Singaporean deaths and infections arising from this. Many families will suffer the consequences.  Please also activate our defence force . The army ambulances should be activated to cope, non-sensitive camps should be used as a “fever centre” to ease the load on Hospitals and GPs.   Please, implement with speed. Take a strong stand, and take risks, that would pay off for the well being of Singaporeans.   Thank you.

It's not xenophobic sentiments that we have. Rather, it's a phobia of a deadly epidemic happening here. And who would be the ones who are most vulnerable?  It's the children, the elderly folks, and those with an already compromised immunity in our families. Even with the help of contact tracing ( which is both time- and resources-consuming) in the aftermath, how likely is it able to get hold of all those who have been in close contact for reasonable amount of time with the infected persons?  And then, by quarantining these close contacts, how much inconvenience it would cause them, their families and their employers ( or industries)? Dear Dr. Lam Pin Min（蓝彬明）good evening.   By way of introductions, I am BK Tan , and travel frequently. As a Singaporean, my immediate concerns are with respect to service staff at the many hotels throughout the island; as well as the safety of our Singapore Cabin Crew and Tech Crew.   Over the past week, as the news updates of the 2019-nCoV was released, many individuals, including myself, have concerns that front line staff throughout the service industry (such as hoteliers and airline crew) whom are the most exposed to the virus are not taking sufficient measures to protect themselves.   I however do not fault these employees since the concern of the everyday Asian (and Singaporean worker) is a fear of backlash and repercussions (from the employer) for making that first step to “protect oneself”.   News reports have shown that the strain we are dealing with today can very well be more potent than SARS. As an ex-employee of the Singapore Airlines group, I have witnessed first hand the impact of a slump in travel due to SARS. Surplus aircraft were parked at the taxiways as space was constrained; staff took a paycut across the board; voluntary retirement schemes were introduced etc.   I keep hearing “we can better manage today’s situation because of the lessons from SARS.” However, have we really?   A Leader is one whom always has the employee’s welfare (health included) at heart. We do not wish to wait for the first accident / casualty because of a mindset that business takes precedence over employee welfare.   Based on clarification (https://www.facebook.com/6352578678/posts/10158135435373679/) I know for a fact that at Singapore Airlines, crew may AT THEIR DISCRETION use masks and disposable gloves when on rostered for China bound flights. Should they wish to, other than within the aircraft cabin, aircrew may wear masks at public areas (hotels and airport terminal); and on crew transport (to/from airport terminal and hotel). I applaud this BUT only on the surface since Management has not made this a MANDATORY requirement.   Whilst good presentation and looks are key for service staff, this surely must now take secondary importance. From this point onwards, at least till we can find a cure for the virus, it must be brains before beauty.   I ask that through the Ministry of Health, Singapore, MAKE IT MANDATORY, for Aircrew to down masks (at minimum) for ALL FLIGHTS, this on the basis that Singapore is a transit hub, for Travelers (including inbound from and outbound to China), flying internationally.   Am confident that the Singapore Ministry of Manpower requires all employers to instill a safe work place environment, and Temasek as Singapore Airlines’* largest shareholder surely would want workplace safety to be always instilled at all times.   On this basis, please consider making it MANDATORY (not optional) for ALL SERVICE STAFF (hoteliers, aircrew etc) the use of masks, gloves and other protection gear (as necessary). Specific for the aircrew, the mandate should be extended for ALL FLIGHTS instead of restricting this to solely CHINA operations. Everyone of us, are well aware of why there is a need for better protection, given the circumstances at hand and only hope for a better and more responsible Management that places emphasis on their front line staff health and safety.   *includes SilkAir and FlyScoot as SQ group wholly owned subsidiaries.

Dear MOH, is it MOH intention or SOP to make elderly wait for at least 3 hours for vaccination? I was bewildered, if you have expected weekends to be so crowded and tedious waiting, why set these seniors appointments on Saturday? Not to mention young people are also allowed to register during this period which I thought is supposed to prioritize the seniors... if not for the staff to suggest we could collect a queue tix, leave for dinner and come back 2 hrs later to take the jab, I would be more annoyed. He has provided an App to show the queue status.   After returning to the CC, my mum had to wait for another hour seated in the indoor auditorium to get the jab.. we were all beat and exhausted, I am sure other seniors and their caregivers also feel the same.

We probably knew someone who was badly hit by the virus in one way or another. We lost our connectivity abroad. Some of us lost even more than that. Today, Singapore is on the road to recovery. We have the people and we know what needs to get done. Bring back our lives and build back better from it. I am extremely moved that the first dedicated facility for travellers has been opened. I note that the task force constantly remind us to stay vigilant and we will indeed continue to stay alert. We have to stay safe and we have each other to cover our backs. Is global mass vaccination really the best and only way forward? . Or is there some herd mentality among global leaders, and public health professionals, with biased favor for "prestigious" "high-tech" vaccines, instead of "low-tech" N95 masks? Or even some profit-driven interest in pushing widespread vaccination instead of widespread N95 mask usage? . Have countries like Singapore tried getting people involved in border control, to have strict N95 mask protocols, before deeming border leaks as inevitable? Or are people like bus drivers and quarantine-hotel staff free to wear whatever random low-effectiveness piece of cloth that they fancy? . Wouldn't widespread N95 mask usage effectively lead to "herd immunity"? (Instead of other low-efficiency masks that keep the virus circulating in lower doses that reduce disease severity and thus evade detection.) . Vaccines: ~$20 each (cost of distribution not yet included). Pros deemed to outweigh the Cons, by the same global group of people who told us sars-cov-2 wasn't airborne, when evidence of airborne transmission of previous coronaviruses was already available but ignored. And while evidence of long-term safety of covid vaccines is absent. And are the ones who earlier rejected widespread mask usage as pointless, thus are psychologically predisposed to not consider widespread mask usage as the actual solution. . Future of reliance on vaccine: Lengthy global "anti-social" measures the next time a virulent airborne disease surfaces, while waiting for vaccine development. Potential for huge profits for Pharm industry if adverse long-term health consequences eventually surface with high frequency. . N95 Masks: ~$1 each, easily reused for a month. Much more politically/morally feasible to force entire populations to use them, compared to the vaccines. Pandemic could have ended months ago, with widespread N95 mask usage, achieving sufficient "herd immunity" for transmission to fizzle out globally. Probably can get 1 N95 mask per person for global population, in 1 month's time.  Child-sized N95 masks can be promptly implemented, unlike vaccines which are neither tested nor implemented on children. . Future of reliance on N95 Masks: Swift implementation to eradicate human-human transmission. Can be stored easily, and for years with negligible decrease in filtration efficiency. . According to scmp news:  An American firm is stuck with 30 million N95 masks, while 90% of mask factories in China were closed (2nd half of 2020).  U.S. guidelines still discourage general population from using N95s. 02月13日 新加坡疫情统计数据报告：新增确诊病例09，累计确诊病例59,833，(包括：累计境外及客工确诊病例56,843、累计社区确诊病例2,943、累计旅客确诊病例47)，累计重症住院病例34(其中累计危重症病例1)，累计死亡病例29，累计确诊轻症隔离病例119，累计治愈病例59,604，死亡率0.04%。 Roylab Stats World Map全球新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例超108,953,518，累计死亡病例超2,400,408，死亡率2.20%。 美国新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例28,125,957，累计死亡病例492,933，死亡率1.75%。占全球确诊率25.81%，占全球死亡率20.53%。马来西亚排列49、中国排列84、新加坡排列96。 疫苗作为抵御病毒全球大流行的终极武器，被人们寄予厚望，疫苗是解决新冠肺炎病毒最根本办法，不管哪个国家做出来疫苗，都不能供应全世界，这需要互相学习，且做出来后取长补短，可能要由很多厂家来生产，才能够供应全世界。世界卫生组织（WHO）呼吁全球合作伙伴共同发起全球合作加速开发、生产、公平获取新冠肺炎防控新工具的倡议。新冠病毒是一种新病毒，疫苗研发有很多不确定因素，多种技术路线并进才是多保险方案，为了更大限度地提升疫苗研发的成功率，在梳理分析不同的技术基础和可能性之后，科研攻关组布局了病毒的灭活疫苗、核酸疫苗、重组蛋白疫苗、腺病毒载体疫苗、减毒流感病毒载体疫苗这样5条技术路线。目前国际上绝大多数疫苗都处于临床研究阶段，中国有4种疫苗即腺病毒载体疫苗和3种灭活疫苗；美国有3种包括莫德纳药企的mRNA疫苗、辉瑞药企的mRNA疫苗、Inovio药企的DNA载体疫苗；英国有1种为牛津大学的腺病毒载体疫苗。 灭活疫苗是最传统的经典技术路线：即在体外培养新冠病毒，然后将其灭活，使之没有毒性，但这些病毒仍能刺激人体产生抗体，使免疫细胞记住病毒的模样，灭活疫苗的优点是制备方法简单快速，安全性比较高，它是应对急性疾病传播通常采用的手段，其缺点如接种剂量大、免疫期短、免疫途径单一等，而有时会造成抗体依赖增强效应（ADE），使病毒感染加重，会导致疫苗研发失败的严重不良反应。 腺病毒载体疫苗是用经过改造后无害的腺病毒作为载体，装入新冠病毒的S蛋白基因，制成腺病毒载体疫苗，刺激人体产生抗体。S蛋白是新冠病毒入侵人体细胞的关键“钥匙”，无害的腺病毒戴上S蛋白的“帽子”，假装自己很“凶”，让人体产生免疫记忆。优点是：安全、高效、引发的不良反应少。这种疫苗有成功先例，缺点，重组病毒载体疫苗研发需要考虑如何克服“预存免疫”，大多数人成长过程中曾感染过5型腺病毒，体内可能存在能中和腺病毒载体的抗体，从而可能攻击载体、降低疫苗效果。 核酸疫苗包括mRNA疫苗和DNA疫苗，是将编码S蛋白的基因，mRNA或DNA直接注入人体，利用人体细胞在人体内合成S蛋白，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于把一份记录详细的病毒档案交给人体的免疫系统。优点是：研制时不需要合成蛋白质或病毒，流程简单，安全性相对比较高，核酸疫苗是全世界都在积极探索的疫苗研发新技术，缺点是：无成功先例，多数国家无法大规模生产，可能因价格较贵而难以普及到低收入国家。 重组蛋白疫苗，也称基因工程重组亚单位疫苗，是通过基因工程方法，大量生产新冠病毒最有可能作为抗原的S蛋白，把它注射到人体，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于不生产完整病毒，而是单独生产很多新冠病毒的关键部件“钥匙”，将其交给人体的免疫系统认识。优点是：安全、高效、可规模化生产，有成功先例，重组亚单位疫苗的缺点是需要找到一个好的表达系统，这很困难。 病毒减毒活疫苗是非常重要的一类疫苗，是低毒性流感病毒戴上新冠病毒S蛋白“帽子”后形成的融合病毒，可以一石二鸟，既能防流感又能防新冠。 每逢佳节倍思亲，挥之不去的怀念，抹之不掉的回忆，音容不忘永常在。树欲静而风不止、子欲养而亲不在。高山仰望止于前、大海无边渡于岸。沉舟侧伴千帆过、病树前头万木春。子鼠疫年千家災、丑牛苗种万民安。

02月12日 新加坡疫情统计数据报告：新增确诊病例18，累计确诊病例59,824，(包括：累计境外及客工确诊病例56,834、累计社区确诊病例2,943、累计旅客确诊病例47)，累计重症住院病例33(其中累计危重症病例1)，累计死亡病例29，累计确诊轻症隔离病例157，累计治愈病例59,558，死亡率0.04%。 Roylab Stats World Map全球新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例超108,356,813，累计死亡病例超2,381,011，死亡率2.19%。 美国新冠病毒疫情统计数据报告：累计确诊病例28,002,240，累计死亡病例486,922，死亡率1.73%。占全球确诊率25.84%，占全球死亡率20.45%。马来西亚排列49、中国排列84、新加坡排列96。 灭活疫苗是最传统的经典技术路线：即在体外培养新冠病毒，然后将其灭活，使之没有毒性，但这些病毒仍能刺激人体产生抗体，使免疫细胞记住病毒的模样，灭活疫苗的优点是制备方法简单快速，安全性比较高，它是应对急性疾病传播通常采用的手段，其缺点如接种剂量大、免疫期短、免疫途径单一等，而有时会造成抗体依赖增强效应（ADE），使病毒感染加重，会导致疫苗研发失败的严重不良反应。 腺病毒载体疫苗是用经过改造后无害的腺病毒作为载体，装入新冠病毒的S蛋白基因，制成腺病毒载体疫苗，刺激人体产生抗体。S蛋白是新冠病毒入侵人体细胞的关键“钥匙”，无害的腺病毒戴上S蛋白的“帽子”，假装自己很“凶”，让人体产生免疫记忆。优点是：安全、高效、引发的不良反应少。这种疫苗有成功先例，缺点，重组病毒载体疫苗研发需要考虑如何克服“预存免疫”，大多数人成长过程中曾感染过5型腺病毒，体内可能存在能中和腺病毒载体的抗体，从而可能攻击载体、降低疫苗效果。 核酸疫苗包括mRNA疫苗和DNA疫苗，是将编码S蛋白的基因，mRNA或DNA直接注入人体，利用人体细胞在人体内合成S蛋白，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于把一份记录详细的病毒档案交给人体的免疫系统。优点是：研制时不需要合成蛋白质或病毒，流程简单，安全性相对比较高，核酸疫苗是全世界都在积极探索的疫苗研发新技术，缺点是：无成功先例，多数国家无法大规模生产，可能因价格较贵而难以普及到低收入国家。 重组蛋白疫苗，也称基因工程重组亚单位疫苗，是通过基因工程方法，大量生产新冠病毒最有可能作为抗原的S蛋白，把它注射到人体，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于不生产完整病毒，而是单独生产很多新冠病毒的关键部件“钥匙”，将其交给人体的免疫系统认识。优点是：安全、高效、可规模化生产，有成功先例，重组亚单位疫苗的缺点是需要找到一个好的表达系统，这很困难。 病毒减毒活疫苗是非常重要的一类疫苗，是低毒性流感病毒戴上新冠病毒S蛋白“帽子”后形成的融合病毒，可以一石二鸟，既能防流感又能防新冠。

新冠病毒是一种新病毒，疫苗研发有很多不确定因素，多种技术路线并进才是多保险方案，为了更大限度地提升疫苗研发的成功率，在梳理分析不同的技术基础和可能性之后，科研攻关组布局了病毒的灭活疫苗、核酸疫苗、重组蛋白疫苗、腺病毒载体疫苗、减毒流感病毒载体疫苗这样5条技术路线。目前国际上绝大多数疫苗都处于临床研究阶段，中国有4种疫苗即腺病毒载体疫苗和3种灭活疫苗；美国有3种包括莫德纳药企的mRNA疫苗、辉瑞药企的mRNA疫苗、Inovio药企的DNA载体疫苗；英国有1种为牛津大学的腺病毒载体疫苗。 灭活疫苗是最传统的经典技术路线：即在体外培养新冠病毒，然后将其灭活，使之没有毒性，但这些病毒仍能刺激人体产生抗体，使免疫细胞记住病毒的模样，灭活疫苗的优点是制备方法简单快速，安全性比较高，它是应对急性疾病传播通常采用的手段，其缺点如接种剂量大、免疫期短、免疫途径单一等，而有时会造成抗体依赖增强效应（ADE），使病毒感染加重，会导致疫苗研发失败的严重不良反应。 腺病毒载体疫苗是用经过改造后无害的腺病毒作为载体，装入新冠病毒的S蛋白基因，制成腺病毒载体疫苗，刺激人体产生抗体。S蛋白是新冠病毒入侵人体细胞的关键“钥匙”，无害的腺病毒戴上S蛋白的“帽子”，假装自己很“凶”，让人体产生免疫记忆。优点是：安全、高效、引发的不良反应少。这种疫苗有成功先例，缺点，重组病毒载体疫苗研发需要考虑如何克服“预存免疫”，大多数人成长过程中曾感染过5型腺病毒，体内可能存在能中和腺病毒载体的抗体，从而可能攻击载体、降低疫苗效果。 核酸疫苗包括mRNA疫苗和DNA疫苗，是将编码S蛋白的基因，mRNA或DNA直接注入人体，利用人体细胞在人体内合成S蛋白，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于把一份记录详细的病毒档案交给人体的免疫系统。优点是：研制时不需要合成蛋白质或病毒，流程简单，安全性相对比较高，核酸疫苗是全世界都在积极探索的疫苗研发新技术，缺点是：无成功先例，多数国家无法大规模生产，可能因价格较贵而难以普及到低收入国家。 重组蛋白疫苗，也称基因工程重组亚单位疫苗，是通过基因工程方法，大量生产新冠病毒最有可能作为抗原的S蛋白，把它注射到人体，刺激人体产生抗体，相当于不生产完整病毒，而是单独生产很多新冠病毒的关键部件“钥匙”，将其交给人体的免疫系统认识。优点是：安全、高效、可规模化生产，有成功先例，重组亚单位疫苗的缺点是需要找到一个好的表达系统，这很困难。 病毒减毒活疫苗是非常重要的一类疫苗，是低毒性流感病毒戴上新冠病毒S蛋白“帽子”后形成的融合病毒，可以一石二鸟，既能防流感又能防新冠。

COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. Scientists tells the truth but politicians suggests otherwise!  ACADEMY OF MEDICINE SINGAPORE, NATIONAL CENTRE FOR INFECTIOUS DISEASE AND COLLEGE OF PHYSICIANS https://www.ams.edu.sg/view-pdf.aspx?file=media%5C5558_fi_168.pdf&ofile=Period+of+Infectivity+Position+Statement+%28final%29+23-5-20.pdf  Sars-CoV-2 virus has not been isolated, purified and cultured. What we get to see are animated cartoon images of the spiked virus.  When the Ct value was 30 or higher (i.e. when viral load is low), no viable virus (based on being able to culture the virus) has been found. In addition, virus could not be isolated or cultured after day 11 of illness — SARS-CoV-2 Virus has not been isolated or cultured, so what is the vaccine for?  PCR machines can't diagnose an infection, it is simply a research tool.  COVID-19 PCR TESTING - FALSE POSITIVES PCR tests cannot be verified for accuracy as there is no ‘gold standard’ against which to check them. The virus has not been purified. (1)  PCR tests cannot detect viral loads and are prone to false positives. (2)  A positive PCR test does not mean that an individual is infected nor infective. (3)  In fact approximately 90% of the PCR positive ‘cases’ are false positives. We therefore have no second wave and no pandemic. (4 , 5)  The government’s report estimates a false positive rate of between 0.8 to 4.0 % using data from other viral infections – not from covid (6)  Viral fragments may remain in people’s bodies for several weeks following recovery from infection. (7)  The crisis will never end if we are waiting for zero positive tests. Everyone has probably had a cold caused by a coronavirus and will likely have a few viral fragments matching those of the cousin SARS-CoV-2 virus (8)  Testing healthy asymptomatic individuals is non-sensical, unscientific and a colossal waste of money.  Antibody testing is not the gold standard as many people have T-cell immunity, and antibodies may not circulate following recovery from infection.  Viral RNA detection by PCR does not equate to infectiousness or viable virus — PCR testings are scientifically meaningless because it is not a diagnostic tool, so why keep testing and testing people?
